oi-tre-tuong-lai/ GS Nguyen Dinh Duc: M\u00f9a Xu\u00e2n - Tu\u1ed5i tr\u1ebb - T\u01b0\u01a1ng lai (Xu\u00e2n \u0110inh D\u1eadu 2017)]\n* [http://dantri.com.vn/giao-duc-khuyen-hoc/nguong-mo-phong-thi-nghiem-made-in-viet-nam-vuon-tam-quoc-te-20170130074919611.htm  PTN c\u1ee7a GS Nguy\u1ec5n \u0110\u00ecnh \u0110\u1ee9c - V\u01b0\u01a1n t\u1ea7m qu\u1ed1c t\u1ebf]\n* [http://dantri.com.vn/giao-duc-khuyen-hoc/gs-nguyen-dinh-duc-nguoi-thay-nha-khoa-hoc-xuat-sac-trong-cong-dong-khoa-hoc-quoc-te-20171118075323931.htm Ng\u01b0\u1eddi th\u1ea7y, nh\u00e0 khoa h\u1ecdc xu\u1ea5t s\u1eafc trong c\u1ed9ng \u0111\u1ed3ng khoa h\u1ecdc qu\u1ed1c t\u1ebf] \n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D1ULaU31DHw About the patent of nanocomposite - Prof. Nguyen Dinh Duc in Vietnam TV]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Duc, Nguyen Dinh}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Moscow State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Vietnamese academics]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nguyen_Dinh_Duc"}
{"title_page": "Porto Torres", "text_new": "{{Infobox Italian comune\n| name                = Porto Torres\n| official_name       = Comune di  Porto Torres\n| native_name         = Posthud\u00f2rra\n|settlement_type=Citt\u00e0| image_skyline       =  Porto Torres, panorama (02).jpg\n| imagesize           = \n| image_alt           = \n| image_caption       = \n| image_shield        = Porto_Torres-Stemma.png\n| shield_alt          = \n| image_map           = \n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = \n| pushpin_map         = Italy Sardinia\n| coordinates         = {{coord|40|50|N|8|24|E|type:city(21,064)_region:IT|display=inline}}\n| coordinates_footnotes = \n| region              = [[Sardinia]]\n| province            = [[Province of Sassari|Sassari]] (SS)\n| frazioni            =Li Lioni, Asinara, Fiume Santo, Platamona \n| mayor_party         =Movimento 5 stelle \n| mayor               = Sean Christian Wheeler\n| area_footnotes      = \n| area_total_km2      = 104.41\n| population_footnotes = <ref name=\"istat\">All demographics and other statistics: Italian statistical institute [[National Institute of Statistics (Italy)|Istat]].</ref>\n| population_total    = 22.016\n| population_as_of    = 30 October 2019 \n| pop_density_footnotes = \n| population_demonym  = Turritani or Portotorresi\n| elevation_footnotes = \n| elevation_m         =17.00 \n|istat=090058| saint               = St. [[Gavinus]] , St. Proto, St. Gianuario\n| day                 = 30 May\n| postal_code         = 07046\n| area_code           = 079\n| website             = {{official website|http://www.comune.porto-torres.ss.it}}\n| footnotes           = \n}}\n'''Porto Torres''' ({{lang-sdc|Posthudorra}}, {{lang-sc|Portu Turre}}) is a ''[[comune]]'' and city in the [[Province of Sassari]], northern [[Sardinia]], [[Italy]].\n\nIt is situated on the north-west coast about {{convert|25|km|mi}} east of the Gorditanian promontory (Capo del Falcone), and on the spacious bay of the [[Gulf of Asinara]].\n\n==Geography==\nPorto Torres' territory is situated on the north-west part of Sardinian Coast.\n[[File:Porto_Torres_scogliera.jpeg|alt=|left|thumb|297x297px|Cliff outside the town.]]\nThe extension of municipality is almost 10200 hectare and is subdivided in two parts, with almost the same extension.\nOne part includes the city, the industrial area and the Roman ruins; the latter is formed by the [[Asinara]] island with the smaller Isola Piana. This part of territory is, since 1997, [[Asinara National Park|a national park]].\n\nThe morphology of \"city part\" is flat; the area of Porto Torres and the rest part of north-west Sardinia is characterized by a [[Nurra]] flat, there are some hill formation in the middle of the flat. Part of this hill formation is in Porto Torres' territory and the highest elevation of it is Monte Alvaro with it thickness of 342&nbsp;m.\n\nThe communal territory is crossed by two rivers, Rio Mannu and Fiume Santo. The first draws the edge of Porto Torres territory on west, while instead the latter flows near the city and was used as a fluvial way as early as the [[ancient Rome|Roman age]].\n\n==History==\n\n[[File:Roman bridge of Turris Libisonis, Porto Torres, Sardinia (16557754949).jpg|thumb|left|Roman bridge.]]\nIn ancient times, '''Turris Libyssonis''' was one of the most considerable cities in Sardinia. It was probably of purely [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] origin, founded apparently by [[Julius Caesar]], as it bore the title ''Colonia Julia''.<ref name=EB1911TurrisLibisonis>{{EB1911|wstitle=Turris Libisonis|inline=1}}</ref>  [[Pliny the Elder|Pliny]] described it as a [[Colonia (Roman)|colony]], the only on the island in his time, suggesting that there was previously no town on the spot, but merely a fort or ''castellum''.<ref>{{harvnb|Smith|1857|p=1241}} Cites: Plin. iii. 12. s. 17.</ref> It is noticed also by [[Ptolemy]] and in the [[Antonine Itinerary|Itineraries]], but without any indication that it was a place of any importance.<ref>{{harvnb|Smith|1857|p=1241}} Cites: Ptol. iii. 3. \u00a7 5; Itin. Ant. p.&nbsp;83.</ref>\n\nThe ancient remains still existing prove that it must have been a considerable town under the [[Roman Empire]]. According to inscriptions on ancient milestones, the principal road through the island ran directly from Caralis ([[Cagliari]]) to Turris, a sufficient proof that the latter was a place much frequented. Indeed, two roads, which diverged at Othoca (modern [[Santa Giusta]]) connected Caralis to Turris, the more important keeping inland and the other following the west coast.<ref name=EB1911TurrisLibisonis/> It was also an [[episcopal see]] during the early part of the Middle Ages.\n\n[[File:San Gavino Aussenansicht.JPG|Basilica of San Gavino|thumb|left|401x401px]]The existing port at Porto Torres, which is almost wholly artificial, is based in great part on Roman foundations; and there exist also the remains of a temple (which, as we learn from an inscription, was dedicated to Fortune, and restored in the reign of [[Philip the Arab|Philip]]), of ''[[Roman bath|thermae]]'', of a basilica and an aqueduct, as well as a bridge over the adjoining small river, still called the ''Fiume Turritano''. The ancient city continued to be inhabited till the 11th century, when the greater part of the population migrated to [[Sassari]], about {{convert|15|km|mi|0}} inland, and situated on a hill.<ref>{{harvnb|Smith|1857|p=1241}} Cites: De la Marmora, ''Voy. en Sardaigne'', vol. ii. pp.&nbsp;363,468-72; Smyth's Sardinia, pp.&nbsp;263-66.</ref> It was partly under [[Republic of Genoa|Genoese]] hands before, in the early 15th century, it was conquered by the [[house of Aragon|Aragonese]]. After the Spanish rule it was part of the [[Kingdom of Sardinia]].\n\nTorres was separated from the comune of Sassari in 1842. At the time the area which had been built around the basilica of San Gavino joined the fishermen's community near the port to form the new ''Porto Torres''.\n<br />\n==Main sights==\n* The 11th-century  [[Basilica of San Gavino]], built using only hardstones like marble, porphyry and granite, is the largest [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] church in Sardinia. Instead of the usual western facade and eastern apse, the cathedral sports two apses. The crypt holds several Roman sarcophagi.\n* Neolithic [[necropolis of Su Crucifissu Mannu]] and [[Li Lioni]].\n* [[Nuraghe]] of [[la Camusina]], [[Li Pedriazzi]], [[Margone]] and [[Minciaredda]].\n* Remains of the Roman bridge, the largest in Sardinia with its arches and a span of {{convert|160|to|170|m|ft}} on the Rio Mannu\n* ''Palazzo Re Barbaro''\n* [[Catacombs]] of Tanca Borgona and ''piazzale Amsicora''.\n* Aragonese Towers of the port and of Abbacurrente.\n\n== Free access beaches ==\n[[File:Spiaggia_di_Balai.jpg|alt=|thumb|Balai beach.|left]]\n<br />The town of Porto Torres has several free access beaches and cliffs suitable for bathing activities. Main beach is the one called \"Balai\" (lit.\"Spiaggia di Balai\").\n\n\n\nOther beaches are :[[File:Turritana_costa.JPG|alt=|thumb|199x199px|Cliff near the town.|left]]\n\n* Renaredda's beach (lit. \"Spiaggia della Renaredda\")\n\n* Scogliolungo's beach (lit.\"Spiaggia dello Scogliolungo\")\n\n* Beach of Acque dolci (lit.\"Spiaggia delle acque dolci\")\n\n* Farrizza's beach (lit.\"Spiaggia di Farrizza\")\n\n* Abbacurrente's beach (lit.\"Spiaggia di Abbacurrente\")\n\n\n\n\n\n\n== Public transport and other connections ==\n[[File:ARST Mercedes-Benz Citaro (9907).jpg|alt=|left|thumb|300x300px|Intercity bus owned by [[ARST (company)|ARST]]. Note that all public intercity buses are deep-blue colored.]]\n<br />\n\n=== Ferries ===\nThe city is connected by [[Ferry|ferries]] with [[Genoa]], [[Marseille]], [[Toulon]], [[Barcelona]], [[Civitavecchia]].In the north-west of Sardinia, the harbor of Porto Torres is the biggest<ref>{{Citation|title=Porto di Porto Torres|date=2020-03-14|url=https://it.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Porto_di_Porto_Torres&oldid=111446452|work=Wikipedia|language=it|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>. In front of the harbor quay there is a large Parking site and not so far from it there is the Maritime Terminal (Stazione marittima). In the same area there is built the new passenger terminal (the building is still under construction).   \n\nThe harbor area is very close to the town's center. The entire space is served with several hotels, B&B, restaurants ,museums, shops, and some 24/7 service areas.  \n\n=== Public transport ===\nPorto Torres belongs to the metropolitan network of north Sardinia (lit. \"Rete metropolitana del nord Sardegna\"<ref>{{Citation|title=Rete metropolitana del Nord Sardegna|date=2020-03-17|url=https://it.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Rete_metropolitana_del_Nord_Sardegna&oldid=111515393|work=Wikipedia|language=it|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>). Due to this, the city is well-connected with all nearly towns via intercity autobus thanks to the [[ARST (company)|ARST]]. Local rides are managed by the local public transport agency (A.t.p. Sassari). Main connection with [[Sassari]] is the [[ARST]]'s intercity line 719 (lit. \"Linea 719\"). Also [[ARST (company)|ARST]] offer a connection with [[Alghero\u2013Fertilia Airport|Alghero's airport]].\n\nIt is possible to buy tickets both in the [[Tobacconist|tobacco shops]] and [[Newsagent's shop|newsagent's shops]]. Tickets can be bought directly into the autobus from the bus driver, but due to local policies the price will be higher. Recently it is possible to buy tickets online using a mobile app<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.atono.dropticket&hl=it|title=DropTicket - App su Google Play|website=play.google.com|language=it|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apps.apple.com/it/app/dropticket/id916708542|title=\u200eDropTicket|website=App\u00a0Store|language=it-it|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>. \n\nLines, timetables and prices can be easily find on [[Google Maps|Google maps]] or in the unofficial [[ARST (company)|ARST]] mobile app<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://arst.sardegna.it/orari_e_autolinee.html|title=ARST - - Orari e linee|website=arst.sardegna.it|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.sardegna.trasporti.arsttrasporti&hl=en_US|title=Orari ARST - Apps on Google Play|website=play.google.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apps.apple.com/it/app/arst-finder/id1465638702|title=\u200eArst Finder|website=App\u00a0Store|language=it-it|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>.<br />\n[[File:Linea PS.jpg|alt=|thumb|301x301px|Autobus owned by the local public transport agency (A.t.p.). Public buses that make only local rides (only into the town) are bright-white colored.|left]]\n\n=== Main roads and highways ===\nHighway SS131/E25  connect the town with the main city [[Sassari]] and the chief town [[Cagliari]]. Also road SS200 lead the way to Santa Teresa Gallura.\n\nSP81 lead to [[Platamona]], [[Sorso]] and Eden beach\n\nSP42 (A.k.a. \"Strada dei due mari\") connect the town with A[[Alghero\u2013Fertilia Airport|lghero's airport]]  and A[[Alghero|lghero]].\n\nThe town has two main roads: Sassari's road (lit. Via Sassari) and Vigne's road (lit. Via delle vigne)\n\nThe main road of the town's center (Piazza Umberto I / Piazza Garibaldi ) is \"Corso Vittorio Emanuele II\" \n\nStreets with panoramic view are \"Via Lungomare Balai\" and \"SP81\".\n\n<br />\n\n=== Train stations ===\nA railway operated by [[Trenitalia]] connects the town with [[Sassari]] and the rest of the island.The town has two train stations, one built at the end of the [[20th century]] (considered as the main station) and one smaller and more historical built during the [[19th century]] (referred as \"Porto Torres marittima\").\n\n== Schools ==\nThe town has many state [[Secondary school|high-schools]] and several state [[Primary school|primary schools]] in its territory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.comune.porto-torres.ss.it/Servizi/Servizi-al-cittadino/Educazione-e-scuola/Scuole-dellobbligo-a-Porto-Torres|title=Scuole dell'obbligo a Porto Torres|last=Torres|first=Comune di Porto|website=Comune di Porto Torres|language=it|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iispaglietti.edu.it/index.php/l-istituto/la-scuola/i-licei/liceo-di-porto-torres|title=Liceo di Porto Torres|last=SSIS00400C|website=www.iispaglietti.edu.it|language=it-it|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nIn the urban territory there is also a [[music school]] named in memory of the italian songwriter [[Fabrizio De Andr\u00e9|Fabrizio de Andr\u00e8]] .<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.comune.porto-torres.ss.it/Servizi/Servizi-al-cittadino/Scuola-Civica-di-Musica-Fabrizio-De-Andre|title=Scuola Civica di Musica|last=Torres|first=Comune di Porto|website=Comune di Porto Torres|language=it|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nDue to the proximity to the city of [[Sassari]] and thanks to the intercity lines managed by [[ARST (company)|ARST]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://arst.sardegna.it/orari_e_autolinee/Servizi_extraurbani.html|title=ARST - - Servizi extraurbani TPL|website=arst.sardegna.it|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> for the citizens is very easy to reach the near [[University of Sassari]].\n\n== Sports ==\n\n\nThere is a large number of [[Dance|Dancing]] and [[Bodybuilding|Bodybuilding gyms]] all around the city. Main sport practiced are:\n\n=== Football ===\nMain football clubs: ''[[A.C. Porto Torres|Porto Torres Calcio]] ([[Serie D]]) ; Turris ; Polisportiva Dilettantistica Quartieri Riuniti (A.k.a. \"Quartieri Riuniti\") ; Turritana''\n\n=== Tennis ===\nMain association: ''Tennis Club Porto Torres''\n\n=== Basket ===\nMain associations: ''GSD Porto Torres; CMB Porto Torres; Silver Basket Porto Torres; Balai Basket''\n\n=== Martial arts and combat sports ===\nThere are many boxing clubs and martial arts schools. Sports like [[Shotokan|Karate shotokan]], [[Mixed martial arts|MMA]], [[Boxing]], [[Jujutsu|Jujitsu]], [[Krav Maga|Krav-Maga]] and [[Self-defense]] are very appreciated and practiced by some part of the citizens.\n\n=== '''Athletics''' ===\nMain association: ''Atletica Leggera Porto Torres (associated with [[Italian Athletics Federation|FIDAL]])''\n<br />\n\n== Facilities ==\n\n* Palasport \"Alberto Mura\" (former \"''Palasport Citt\u00e0 Unite''\")\n* Tennis club \n* Boxing club \"Alberto Mura\"\n* Hostel Balai (formerly \"''Ostello della giovent\u00f9''\")\n* Municipal stadium \n* Skate park\n\n== Parks and plazas ==\n\n* ''Parco [[Gavinus|San Gavino]] -'' Considered as the main park, It is served with many [[Playground|plays]] for children.\n* ''Parco [[Robert Baden-Powell, 1st Baron Baden-Powell|Robert Baden-Powell]] -'' Very large park between Tramontana's road and the SP81''.'' It is served with some parking sites.\n* ''Parco per cani [[Robert Baden-Powell, 1st Baron Baden-Powell|Robert Baden-Powell]] -'' The south part of the ''Parco [[Robert Baden-Powell, 1st Baron Baden-Powell|Robert Baden-Powell]],'' used as a dog park.\n* ''Parco [[Chico Mendes]] -'' Small park behind the ''Hostel Balai.''\n* ''Parco Balai vicino -'' Green area behind the famous ''Balai beach.'' Used for events during the summer.\n* ''Pineta Balai lontano -'' Large artificial pine forest used to do outdoor activities. It was planted during the [[Italian Fascism|Fascist regime]].\n\n* ''Piazza [[Umberto I of Italy|Umberto I]] (''A.k.a''. Piazza del comune / Piazza mercato) -'' Main plaza of Porto Torres where there is located the [[Town hall|Town Hall]].\n\n[[File:Balai.jpeg.jpg|alt=|thumb|''Parco Balai lontano'']]\n\n* ''Piazza [[Giuseppe Garibaldi]] (''Simply as ''Piazza Garibaldi) -'' Considered as the second main plaza of the town, It is served with many restaurants and taverns.\n\n*''Piazza dell Consolata -'' Right in front of ''Piazza Umberto I,'' in the other side of ''Corso Vittorio Emanuele II.''\n*''Piazza [[Capture of Rome|XX Settembre]] -'' The small plaza at the end of ''Corso Vittorio Emanuele II,'' considered as one of the main meeting point. It is served with many restaurants and pubs.\n*''Piazza Dogana -'' An historical plaza in front of the harbor mainly used as a Parking site.\n\n* ''Piazza [[Christopher Columbus|Cristoforo Colombo]]'' (Simply as ''Piazza Colombo'') - In front of the historical Spanish tower.\n[[File:Pineta_pt.jpeg|alt=|left|thumb|''Pineta Balai lontano'']]\n\n* ''Piazza [[Luigi Luzzatti]] -'' A small plaza mostly occupied by a Gas station.\n\n* ''Piazza Eroi dell'onda''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lanuovasardegna.it/sassari/cronaca/2012/09/18/news/gli-eroi-dell-onda-nel-43-pescarono-il-sommergibile-1.5717989|title=Gli eroi dell\u2019Onda: nel \u201943 pescarono il sommergibile|date=2012-09-19|website=La Nuova Sardegna|language=it-IT|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> (A.k.a ''Piazza della Renaredda'') - The large plaza near the Renaredda's beach, It is served with a basketball camp. Nearly there is a 24/7 service area.\n\n*''Piazza [[Guglielmo Marconi]]'' (Simply as ''Piazza Marconi'') -  Small plaza near the Basilica of San Gavino.\n*''Piazza Martiri Turritani'' (referred to [[Gavinus]], Proto, Gianuario) - Small plaza behind the Basilica of San Gavino and near ''[[Gavinus|San Gavino]]'s park.''\n*''Piazza Cagliari 1970'' (referred to [[1969\u201370 Cagliari Calcio season]]) - Plaza in front of the municipal stadium used as a parking site.\n\n* Piazza [[Hampsicora|Amsicora]] - Small plaza used as a parking site.\n\n== Asinara National Park ==\n{{See also|Asinara National Park}}\n\n== Economy and industry ==\n\nChemical industries support the modern economy of Porto Torres. Fiume Santo, a 1,040 MW power station owned by [[E.ON]], is {{convert|5|to|10|km|mi|0}} west from the city, in the [[Sassari|municipality of Sassari]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.power-technology.com/projects/fiume-santo/|title=Fiume Santo Power Station (Thermoelectric Power Plant), Italy|accessdate=28 January 2011}}</ref>\n[[File:Cementificio_Porto_Torres.jpeg|alt=|thumb|300x300px|Factory abandoned for decades.]]\n<br />\n[[File:Areaindustrialeportotorres.jpg|alt=|left|thumb|300x300px|Industrial zone in the early [[21st century]].]]\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nPlans related to industrial conversion are in progress in Porto Torres, where seven research centers are developing the transformation from traditional fossil fuel related industry to an integrated production chain from vegetable oil using oleaginous seeds to bio-plastics.<ref>[http://www.eni.com/it_IT/attachments/azienda/attivita-strategie/petrolchimica/polimeri-europa/pubblicazioni/Versalis-Brochure-istituzionale-per-il-Plast12.pdf matrica: green chemicals]</ref><ref>[http://www.icis.com/Articles/2012/04/23/9552160/a-new-age-for-the-italian-chemical-industry.html A new age for the Italian chemical industry]</ref>\n\n== Curiosity ==\n\n* Legends says that the original ''Colonia Iulia Turris Libisonis'' was founded by the will of [[Augustus|Gaius Octavius]] of the [[Julia (gens)|Gens Juilia]]. Probably the real founder of the city was one of his collaborator, ''Marcus Lurius,'' in the 46 b.C.<ref>{{Citation|title=Porto Torres|date=2020-04-06|url=https://it.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Porto_Torres&oldid=111994903|work=Wikipedia|language=it|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* In May 1943 dictator [[Benito Mussolini]] has visited the town. In the [[Istituto Luce|Luce]]'s archive there are many photos about this event, including one where there is clearly visible the iconic tower of the city<ref>{{Citation|last=Careddu|first=Gianni|title=Italiano: Porto Torres - Torre del Porto|date=2012-05-01|url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Porto_Torres_-_Torre_del_Porto_(2).jpg|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://senato.archivioluce.it/senato-luce/scheda/foto/IL3000006141/12/Mussolini-a-Porto-Torres.html|title=Mussolini a Porto Torres - Reparto Attualit\u00e0 - Scheda fotografica - Istituto Luce - Cinecitt\u00e0 - Senato della Repubblica|website=senato.archivioluce.it|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>.\n\n\n\nReferences\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{commons category|Porto Torres}}\n*{{SmithDGRG |wstitle=Turris Libyssonis |volume=2 |page=1241}}\n\n{{Province of Sassari}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Communes of the Province of Sassari]]\n[[Category:Roman towns and cities in Italy]]\n[[Category:1842 establishments in the Kingdom of Sardinia]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1842]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Italian comune\n| name                = Porto Torres\n| official_name       = Comune di  Porto Torres\n| native_name         = Posthud\u00f2rra\n|settlement_type=Citt\u00e0| image_skyline       =  Porto Torres, panorama (02).jpg\n| imagesize           = \n| image_alt           = \n| image_caption       = \n| image_shield        = Porto_Torres-Stemma.png\n| shield_alt          = \n| image_map           = \n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = \n| pushpin_map         = Italy Sardinia\n| coordinates         = {{coord|40|50|N|8|24|E|type:city(21,064)_region:IT|display=inline}}\n| coordinates_footnotes = \n| region              = [[Sardinia]]\n| province            = [[Province of Sassari|Sassari]] (SS)\n| frazioni            =Li Lioni, Asinara, Fiume Santo, Platamona \n| mayor_party         =Movimento 5 stelle \n| mayor               = Sean Christian Wheeler\n| area_footnotes      = \n| area_total_km2      = 104.41\n| population_footnotes = <ref name=\"istat\">All demographics and other statistics: Italian statistical institute [[National Institute of Statistics (Italy)|Istat]].</ref>\n| population_total    = 22.016\n| population_as_of    = 30 October 2019 \n| pop_density_footnotes = \n| population_demonym  = Turritani or Portotorresi\n| elevation_footnotes = \n| elevation_m         =17.00 \n|istat=090058| saint               = St. [[Gavinus]] , St. Proto, St. Gianuario\n| day                 = 30 May\n| postal_code         = 07046\n| area_code           = 079\n| website             = {{official website|http://www.comune.porto-torres.ss.it}}\n| footnotes           = \n}}\n'''Porto Torres''' ({{lang-sdc|Posthudorra}}, {{lang-sc|Portu Turre}}) is a ''[[comune]]'' and city in the [[Province of Sassari]], northern [[Sardinia]], [[Italy]].\n\nIt is situated on the north-west coast about {{convert|25|km|mi}} east of the Gorditanian promontory (Capo del Falcone), and on the spacious bay of the [[Gulf of Asinara]].\n\n==Geography==\nPorto Torres' territory is situated on the north-west part of Sardinian Coast.\n[[File:Porto_Torres_scogliera.jpeg|alt=|left|thumb|297x297px|Cliff outside the town.]]\nThe extension of municipality is almost 10200 hectare and is subdivided in two parts, with almost the same extension.\nOne part includes the city, the industrial area and the Roman ruins; the latter is formed by the [[Asinara]] island with the smaller Isola Piana. This part of territory is, since 1997, [[Asinara National Park|a national park]].\n\nThe morphology of \"city part\" is flat; the area of Porto Torres and the rest part of north-west Sardinia is characterized by a [[Nurra]] flat, there are some hill formation in the middle of the flat. Part of this hill formation is in Porto Torres' territory and the highest elevation of it is Monte Alvaro with it thickness of 342&nbsp;m.\n\nThe communal territory is crossed by two rivers, Rio Mannu and Fiume Santo. The first draws the edge of Porto Torres territory on west, while instead the latter flows near the city and was used as a fluvial way as early as the [[ancient Rome|Roman age]].\n\n==History==\n\n[[File:Roman bridge of Turris Libisonis, Porto Torres, Sardinia (16557754949).jpg|thumb|left|Roman bridge.]]\nIn ancient times, '''Turris Libyssonis''' was one of the most considerable cities in Sardinia. It was probably of purely [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] origin, founded apparently by [[Julius Caesar]], as it bore the title ''Colonia Julia''.<ref name=EB1911TurrisLibisonis>{{EB1911|wstitle=Turris Libisonis|inline=1}}</ref>  [[Pliny the Elder|Pliny]] described it as a [[Colonia (Roman)|colony]], the only on the island in his time, suggesting that there was previously no town on the spot, but merely a fort or ''castellum''.<ref>{{harvnb|Smith|1857|p=1241}} Cites: Plin. iii. 12. s. 17.</ref> It is noticed also by [[Ptolemy]] and in the [[Antonine Itinerary|Itineraries]], but without any indication that it was a place of any importance.<ref>{{harvnb|Smith|1857|p=1241}} Cites: Ptol. iii. 3. \u00a7 5; Itin. Ant. p.&nbsp;83.</ref>\n\nThe ancient remains still existing prove that it must have been a considerable town under the [[Roman Empire]]. According to inscriptions on ancient milestones, the principal road through the island ran directly from Caralis ([[Cagliari]]) to Turris, a sufficient proof that the latter was a place much frequented. Indeed, two roads, which diverged at Othoca (modern [[Santa Giusta]]) connected Caralis to Turris, the more important keeping inland and the other following the west coast.<ref name=EB1911TurrisLibisonis/> It was also an [[episcopal see]] during the early part of the Middle Ages.\n\n[[File:San Gavino Aussenansicht.JPG|Basilica of San Gavino|thumb|left|401x401px]]The existing port at Porto Torres, which is almost wholly artificial, is based in great part on Roman foundations; and there exist also the remains of a temple (which, as we learn from an inscription, was dedicated to Fortune, and restored in the reign of [[Philip the Arab|Philip]]), of ''[[Roman bath|thermae]]'', of a basilica and an aqueduct, as well as a bridge over the adjoining small river, still called the ''Fiume Turritano''. The ancient city continued to be inhabited till the 11th century, when the greater part of the population migrated to [[Sassari]], about {{convert|15|km|mi|0}} inland, and situated on a hill.<ref>{{harvnb|Smith|1857|p=1241}} Cites: De la Marmora, ''Voy. en Sardaigne'', vol. ii. pp.&nbsp;363,468-72; Smyth's Sardinia, pp.&nbsp;263-66.</ref> It was partly under [[Republic of Genoa|Genoese]] hands before, in the early 15th century, it was conquered by the [[house of Aragon|Aragonese]]. After the Spanish rule it was part of the [[Kingdom of Sardinia]].\n\nTorres was separated from the comune of Sassari in 1842. At the time the area which had been built around the basilica of San Gavino joined the fishermen's community near the port to form the new ''Porto Torres''.\n<br />\n==Main sights==\n* The 11th-century  [[Basilica of San Gavino]], built using only hardstones like marble, porphyry and granite, is the largest [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] church in Sardinia. Instead of the usual western facade and eastern apse, the cathedral sports two apses. The crypt holds several Roman sarcophagi.\n* Neolithic [[necropolis of Su Crucifissu Mannu]] and [[Li Lioni]].\n* [[Nuraghe]] of [[la Camusina]], [[Li Pedriazzi]], [[Margone]] and [[Minciaredda]].\n* Remains of the Roman bridge, the largest in Sardinia with its arches and a span of {{convert|160|to|170|m|ft}} on the Rio Mannu\n* ''Palazzo Re Barbaro''\n* [[Catacombs]] of Tanca Borgona and ''piazzale Amsicora''.\n* Aragonese Towers of the port and of Abbacurrente.\n\n== Free access beaches ==\n[[File:Spiaggia_di_Balai.jpg|alt=|thumb|Balai beach.|left]]\n<br />The town of Porto Torres has several free access beaches and cliffs suitable for bathing activities. Main beach is the one called \"Balai\" (lit.\"Spiaggia di Balai\").\n\n\n\nOther beaches are :[[File:Turritana_costa.JPG|alt=|thumb|199x199px|Cliff near the town.|left]]\n\n* Renaredda's beach (lit. \"Spiaggia della Renaredda\")\n\n* Scogliolungo's beach (lit.\"Spiaggia dello Scogliolungo\")\n\n* Beach of Acque dolci (lit.\"Spiaggia delle acque dolci\")\n\n* Farrizza's beach (lit.\"Spiaggia di Farrizza\")\n\n* Abbacurrente's beach (lit.\"Spiaggia di Abbacurrente\")\n\n\n\n\n\n\n== Public transport and other connections ==\n[[File:ARST Mercedes-Benz Citaro (9907).jpg|alt=|left|thumb|300x300px|Intercity bus owned by [[ARST (company)|ARST]]. Note that all public intercity buses are deep-blue colored.]]\n<br />\n\n=== Ferries ===\nThe city is connected by [[Ferry|ferries]] with [[Genoa]], [[Marseille]], [[Toulon]], [[Barcelona]], [[Civitavecchia]].In the north-west of Sardinia, the harbor of Porto Torres is the biggest<ref>{{Citation|title=Porto di Porto Torres|date=2020-03-14|url=https://it.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Porto_di_Porto_Torres&oldid=111446452|work=Wikipedia|language=it|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>. In front of the harbor quay there is a large Parking site and not so far from it there is the Maritime Terminal (Stazione marittima). In the same area there is built the new passenger terminal (the building is still under construction).   \n\nThe harbor area is very close to the town's center. The entire space is served with several hotels, B&B, restaurants ,museums, shops, and some 24/7 service areas.  \n\n=== Public transport ===\nPorto Torres belongs to the metropolitan network of north Sardinia (lit. \"Rete metropolitana del nord Sardegna\"<ref>{{Citation|title=Rete metropolitana del Nord Sardegna|date=2020-03-17|url=https://it.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Rete_metropolitana_del_Nord_Sardegna&oldid=111515393|work=Wikipedia|language=it|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>). Due to this, the city is well-connected with all nearly towns via intercity autobus thanks to the [[ARST (company)|ARST]]. Local rides are managed by the local public transport agency (A.t.p. Sassari). Main connection with [[Sassari]] is the [[ARST]]'s intercity line 719 (lit. \"Linea 719\"). Also [[ARST (company)|ARST]] offer a connection with [[Alghero\u2013Fertilia Airport|Alghero's airport]].\n\nIt is possible to buy tickets both in the [[Tobacconist|tobacco shops]] and [[Newsagent's shop|newsagent's shops]]. Tickets can be bought directly into the autobus from the bus driver, but due to local policies the price will be higher. Recently it is possible to buy tickets online using a mobile app<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.atono.dropticket&hl=it|title=DropTicket - App su Google Play|website=play.google.com|language=it|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apps.apple.com/it/app/dropticket/id916708542|title=\u200eDropTicket|website=App\u00a0Store|language=it-it|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>. \n\nLines, timetables and prices can be easily find on [[Google Maps|Google maps]] or in the unofficial [[ARST (company)|ARST]] mobile app<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://arst.sardegna.it/orari_e_autolinee.html|title=ARST - - Orari e linee|website=arst.sardegna.it|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.sardegna.trasporti.arsttrasporti&hl=en_US|title=Orari ARST - Apps on Google Play|website=play.google.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apps.apple.com/it/app/arst-finder/id1465638702|title=\u200eArst Finder|website=App\u00a0Store|language=it-it|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>.<br />\n[[File:Linea PS.jpg|alt=|thumb|301x301px|Autobus owned by the local public transport agency (A.t.p.). Public buses that make only local rides (only into the town) are bright-white colored.|left]]\n\n=== Main roads and highways ===\nHighway SS131/E25  connect the town with the main city [[Sassari]] and the chief town [[Cagliari]]. Also road SS200 lead the way to Santa Teresa Gallura.\n\nSP81 lead to [[Platamona]], [[Sorso]] and Eden beach\n\nSP42 (A.k.a. \"Strada dei due mari\") connect the town with A[[Alghero\u2013Fertilia Airport|lghero's airport]]  and A[[Alghero|lghero]].\n\nThe town has two main roads: Sassari's road (lit. Via Sassari) and Vigne's road (lit. Via delle vigne)\n\nThe main road of the town's center (Piazza Umberto I / Piazza Garibaldi ) is \"Corso Vittorio Emanuele II\" \n\nStreets with panoramic view are \"Via Lungomare Balai\" and \"SP81\".\n\n<br />\n\n=== Train stations ===\nA railway operated by [[Trenitalia]] connects the town with [[Sassari]] and the rest of the island.The town has two train stations, one built at the end of the [[20th century]] (considered as the main station) and one smaller and more historical built during the [[19th century]] (referred as \"Porto Torres marittima\").\n\n== Schools ==\nThe town has many state [[Secondary school|high-schools]] and several state [[Primary school|primary schools]] in its territory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.comune.porto-torres.ss.it/Servizi/Servizi-al-cittadino/Educazione-e-scuola/Scuole-dellobbligo-a-Porto-Torres|title=Scuole dell'obbligo a Porto Torres|last=Torres|first=Comune di Porto|website=Comune di Porto Torres|language=it|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iispaglietti.edu.it/index.php/l-istituto/la-scuola/i-licei/liceo-di-porto-torres|title=Liceo di Porto Torres|last=SSIS00400C|website=www.iispaglietti.edu.it|language=it-it|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nIn the urban territory there is also a [[music school]] named in memory of the italian songwriter [[Fabrizio De Andr\u00e9|Fabrizio de Andr\u00e8]] .<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.comune.porto-torres.ss.it/Servizi/Servizi-al-cittadino/Scuola-Civica-di-Musica-Fabrizio-De-Andre|title=Scuola Civica di Musica|last=Torres|first=Comune di Porto|website=Comune di Porto Torres|language=it|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nDue to the proximity to the city of [[Sassari]] and thanks to the intercity lines managed by [[ARST (company)|ARST]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://arst.sardegna.it/orari_e_autolinee/Servizi_extraurbani.html|title=ARST - - Servizi extraurbani TPL|website=arst.sardegna.it|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> for the citizens is very easy to reach the near [[University of Sassari]].\n\n== Sports ==\n\n\nThere is a large number of [[Dance|Dancing]] and [[Bodybuilding|Bodybuilding gyms]] all around the city. Main sport practiced are:\n\n=== Football ===\nMain football clubs: ''[[A.C. Porto Torres|Porto Torres Calcio]] ([[Serie D]]) ; Turris ; Polisportiva Dilettantistica Quartieri Riuniti (A.k.a. \"Quartieri Riuniti\") ; Turritana''\n\n=== Tennis ===\nMain association: ''Tennis Club Porto Torres''\n\n=== Basket ===\nMain associations: ''GSD Porto Torres; CMB Porto Torres; Silver Basket Porto Torres; Balai Basket''\n\n=== Martial arts and combat sports ===\nThere are many boxing clubs and martial arts schools. Sports like [[Shotokan|Karate shotokan]], [[Mixed martial arts|MMA]], [[Boxing]], [[Jujutsu|Jujitsu]], [[Krav Maga|Krav-Maga]] and [[Self-defense]] are very appreciated and practiced by some part of the citizens.\n\n=== '''Athletics''' ===\nMain association: ''Atletica Leggera Porto Torres (associated with [[Italian Athletics Federation|FIDAL]])''\n<br />\n\n== Facilities ==\n\n* Palasport \"Alberto Mura\" (former \"''Palasport Citt\u00e0 Unite''\")\n* Tennis club \n* Boxing club \"Alberto Mura\"\n* Hostel Balai (formerly \"''Ostello della giovent\u00f9''\")\n* Municipal stadium \n* Skate park\n\n== Parks and plazas ==\n\n* ''Parco [[Gavinus|San Gavino]] -'' Considered as the main park, It is served with many [[Playground|plays]] for children.\n* ''Parco [[Robert Baden-Powell, 1st Baron Baden-Powell|Robert Baden-Powell]] -'' Very large park between Tramontana's road and the SP81''.'' It is served with some parking sites.\n* ''Parco per cani [[Robert Baden-Powell, 1st Baron Baden-Powell|Robert Baden-Powell]] -'' The south part of the ''Parco [[Robert Baden-Powell, 1st Baron Baden-Powell|Robert Baden-Powell]],'' used as a dog park.\n* ''Parco [[Chico Mendes]] -'' Small park behind the ''Hostel Balai.''\n* ''Parco Balai vicino -'' Green area behind the famous ''Balai beach.'' Used for events during the summer.\n* ''Pineta Balai lontano -'' Large artificial pine forest used to do outdoor activities. It was planted during the [[Italian Fascism|Fascist regime]].\n\n* ''Piazza [[Umberto I of Italy|Umberto I]] (''A.k.a''. Piazza del comune / Piazza mercato) -'' Main plaza of Porto Torres where there is located the [[Town hall|Town Hall]].\n\n[[File:Balai.jpeg.jpg|alt=|thumb|''Parco Balai lontano'']]\n\n* ''Piazza [[Giuseppe Garibaldi]] (''Simply as ''Piazza Garibaldi) -'' Considered as the second main plaza of the town, It is served with many restaurants and taverns.\n\n*''Piazza dell Consolata -'' Right in front of ''Piazza Umberto I,'' in the other side of ''Corso Vittorio Emanuele II.''\n*''Piazza [[Capture of Rome|XX Settembre]] -'' The small plaza at the end of ''Corso Vittorio Emanuele II,'' considered as one of the main meeting point. It is served with many restaurants and pubs.\n*''Piazza Dogana -'' An historical plaza in front of the harbor mainly used as a Parking site.\n\n* ''Piazza [[Christopher Columbus|Cristoforo Colombo]]'' (Simply as ''Piazza Colombo'') - In front of the historical Spanish tower.\n[[File:Pineta_pt.jpeg|alt=|left|thumb|''Pineta Balai lontano'']]\n\n* ''Piazza [[Luigi Luzzatti]] -'' A small plaza mostly occupied by a Gas station.\n\n* ''Piazza Eroi dell'onda''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lanuovasardegna.it/sassari/cronaca/2012/09/18/news/gli-eroi-dell-onda-nel-43-pescarono-il-sommergibile-1.5717989|title=Gli eroi dell\u2019Onda: nel \u201943 pescarono il sommergibile|date=2012-09-19|website=La Nuova Sardegna|language=it-IT|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> (A.k.a ''Piazza della Renaredda'') - The large plaza near the Renaredda's beach, It is served with a basketball camp. Nearly there is a 24/7 service area.\n\n*''Piazza [[Guglielmo Marconi]]'' (Simply as ''Piazza Marconi'') -  Small plaza near the Basilica of San Gavino.\n*''Piazza Martiri Turritani'' (referred to [[Gavinus]], Proto, Gianuario) - Small plaza behind the Basilica of San Gavino and near ''[[Gavinus|San Gavino]]'s park.''\n*''Piazza Cagliari 1970'' (referred to [[1969\u201370 Cagliari Calcio season]]) - Plaza in front of the municipal stadium used as a parking site.\n\n* Piazza [[Hampsicora|Amsicora]] - Small plaza used as a parking site.\n\n== Asinara National Park ==\n{{See also|Asinara National Park}}\n\n== Economy and industry ==\n\nChemical industries support the modern economy of Porto Torres. Fiume Santo, a 1,040 MW power station owned by [[E.ON]], is {{convert|5|to|10|km|mi|0}} west from the city, in the [[Sassari|municipality of Sassari]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.power-technology.com/projects/fiume-santo/|title=Fiume Santo Power Station (Thermoelectric Power Plant), Italy|accessdate=28 January 2011}}</ref>\n[[File:Cementificio_Porto_Torres.jpeg|alt=|thumb|300x300px|Factory abandoned for decades.]]\n<br />\n[[File:Areaindustrialeportotorres.jpg|alt=|left|thumb|300x300px|Industrial zone in the early [[21st century|21th century]].]]\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nPlans related to industrial conversion are in progress in Porto Torres, where seven research centers are developing the transformation from traditional fossil fuel related industry to an integrated production chain from vegetable oil using oleaginous seeds to bio-plastics.<ref>[http://www.eni.com/it_IT/attachments/azienda/attivita-strategie/petrolchimica/polimeri-europa/pubblicazioni/Versalis-Brochure-istituzionale-per-il-Plast12.pdf matrica: green chemicals]</ref><ref>[http://www.icis.com/Articles/2012/04/23/9552160/a-new-age-for-the-italian-chemical-industry.html A new age for the Italian chemical industry]</ref>\n== Curiosity ==\n\n* Legends says that the original ''Colonia Iulia Turris Libisonis'' was founded by the will of [[Augustus|Gaius Octavius]] of the [[Julia (gens)|Gens Juilia]]. Probably the real founder of the city was one of his collaborator, ''Marcus Lurius,'' in the 46 b.C.<ref>{{Citation|title=Porto Torres|date=2020-04-06|url=https://it.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Porto_Torres&oldid=111994903|work=Wikipedia|language=it|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* In May 1943 dictator [[Benito Mussolini]] has visited the town. In the [[Istituto Luce|Luce]]'s archive there are many photos about this event, including one where there is clearly visible the iconic tower of the city<ref>{{Citation|last=Careddu|first=Gianni|title=Italiano: Porto Torres - Torre del Porto|date=2012-05-01|url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Porto_Torres_-_Torre_del_Porto_(2).jpg|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://senato.archivioluce.it/senato-luce/scheda/foto/IL3000006141/12/Mussolini-a-Porto-Torres.html|title=Mussolini a Porto Torres - Reparto Attualit\u00e0 - Scheda fotografica - Istituto Luce - Cinecitt\u00e0 - Senato della Repubblica|website=senato.archivioluce.it|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>.\n\n\n\nReferences\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{commons category|Porto Torres}}\n*{{SmithDGRG |wstitle=Turris Libyssonis |volume=2 |page=1241}}\n\n{{Province of Sassari}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Communes of the Province of Sassari]]\n[[Category:Roman towns and cities in Italy]]\n[[Category:1842 establishments in the Kingdom of Sardinia]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1842]]\n", "name_user": "EdmundT", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEconomy and industry:Spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Porto_Torres"}
{"title_page": "Microids", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Microids\n| logo = Microids-Logo.png\n| former_name = {{Unbulleted list|Micro\u00efds (1985\u20132003; 2007\u20132019)|MC2-Micro\u00efds (2003\u20132005)|MC2 (2005\u20132007)}}\n| type = [[Subsidiary]]\n| industry = [[Video game industry|Video games]]\n| founded = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1985}} in [[V\u00e9lizy-Villacoublay]], France\n| founder = Elliot Grassiano\n| hq_location_city = [[Paris]]\n| hq_location_country = France\n| key_people = {{Unbulleted list|St\u00e9phane Longeard ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])|Elliot Grassiano ([[Vice-president|VP]])}}\n| num_employees =\n| num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) -->\n| parent = {{Unbulleted list|Anuman Interactive (2010\u20132019)|[[M\u00e9dia-Participations]] (2019\u2013present)}}\n| website = {{URL|https://www.microids.com/|microids.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Microids''' (formerly '''Micro\u00efds''') is a French [[video game developer]] and [[Video game publisher|publisher]] based in [[Paris]]. Founded in 1985 by Elliot Grassiano, it attained early success with games published through [[Loriciel]] in France and other partners (including [[Activision]] and [[Broderbund]]) in international markets. Through expanding its staff and development teams, Micro\u00efds generated funds to expand from just development to [[Video game publishing|publishing]] and [[Wholesaling|distribution]] and opening international offices. The company merged with MC2 in 2003 to create MC2-Micro\u00efds, whereafter it acquired publishers Wanadoo Edition and [[Cryo Interactive]]. Grassiano left MC2-Micro\u00efds in 2005; under new management, MC2-Micro\u00efds was briefly renamed MC2 before returning to the old Micro\u00efds name. It was then acquired by Anuman Interactive in 2010, which itself was renamed Micro\u00efds (then simplified to Microids) in 2019.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Background and early years (1985\u20132003) ===\nMicro\u00efds was founded by Elliot Grassiano, a French [[Video game programmer|programmer]]. He was educated at the [[Lyc\u00e9e Louis-le-Grand]] school from 1972 to 1974 and later studied engineering, electronics, and computers at the [[\u00c9cole nationale sup\u00e9rieure d'arts et m\u00e9tiers]]. He started working as an engineer for the defence system company [[SAGEM]] in 1979. By the 1980s, Grassiano had become interested in [[telecommunications]], [[consumer electronics]], and video games. He acquired a [[Thomson MO5]]-model [[home computer]], which he used to create his first game, ''Space Shuttle Simulator''. The game was published by [[Loriciel]] and released to both critical and commercial success. Subsequently, Grassiano quit his job to establish his own company. He formally founded Micro\u00efds in 1985, setting it up in [[V\u00e9lizy-Villacoublay]], a suburb of [[Paris]]. He was aided in these efforts by Loriciel's founders, Laurent Weill and Marc Bayle, as well as Patrick Le Nestour, another engineer. The name \"Micro\u00efds\" was a [[portmanteau]] of \"microinformatique\" (\"micro-informatics\") and \"androids\". Within its first year of operation, the company grew to five people, with Grassiano in the managerial role.<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 154\">{{cite magazine |title=From the Archives: Micro\u00efds |first=David |last=Crookes |magazine=[[Retro Gamer]] |issue=154 |publisher=[[Imagine Publishing]] |date=21 April 2016 |pages=50\u201355}}</ref>\n\nInitially, Micro\u00efds set out to create consumer [[robotics]] projects before shifting its focus solely to video games. The first Micro\u00efds-developed game was ''Air Attack'', released by Loriciel for the Thomson MO5 to moderate commercial success. Early [[adventure game]]s developed by Micro\u00efds include ''Oceania'' (developed by Le Nestour and released in 1985 for the Thomson MO5 and [[Thomson TO7|TO7]]) and ''Les Pyramides D'Atlantys'' (developed by Luc Thibaud and released for the [[Amstrad CPC]] in 1986). ''Air Attack'' provided the groundwork for subsequent Micro\u00efds games, such as ''[[500 cc Grand Prix]]'' for the Amstrad CPC, which debuted in 1986. This game was the company's first breakthrough title, partially driven by the CPC's success in France. By way of a deal between Loriciel and [[Activision]], the game was also released in the UK, it was also released in the US, and it was later [[Porting|ported]] to other systems, such as the [[Atari ST]]. The American market appeared especially viable for Micro\u00efds, who believed that game sales would vastly outnumber the domestic ones. For this reason, it partnered with the American publisher [[Broderbund]] in 1987, which released several Micro\u00efds games in the country, partially under altered names. In return, Micro\u00efds managed sales of Broderbund's games, notably ''[[Prince of Persia (1989 video game)|Prince of Persia]]'' and ''[[Karateka (video game)|Karateka]]'' in France.<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 154\" />\n\nThroughout the 1990s, Micro\u00efds underwent expansion, increasing both staff count and development team sizes. Development operations were accelerated to output more games, leading to increased profits. Through the new-earned funds, the company commenced operations in both [[video game publishing]] and [[Wholesaling|distribution]] in 1995, and between then and 1997 opened three international subsidiaries: Micro\u00efds Italia in [[Milan]], Micro\u00efds UK in [[Milton Keynes]], and Micro\u00efds Canada in [[Montreal]]. By 1997, Micro\u00efds had 20 employees and a turnover of 20&nbsp;million [[French franc]]s. Both increased tenfold by 2002, and the Canadian studio alone house 105 of Micro\u00efds' 200 employees by 2003.<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 154\" />\n\n=== Mergers (2003\u2013present) ===\nIn 2003, Micro\u00efds merged with MC2, a French software company, with the amalgam assuming the name MC2-Micro\u00efds.<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 154\" /> In September that year, it acquired Wanadoo Edition, the games division of [[Wanadoo]], which itself had been created through a September 2000 merger between Index+ and France Telecom Multimedia in exchange, Wanadoo received a 12% stake in MC2-Micro\u00efds.<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 154\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://adventuregamers.com/news/view/19154 |title=Microids takes over Wanadoo's games division |first=Marek |last=Bronstring |date=2 October 2003 |website=[[Adventure Gamers]] |access-date=22 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191022223812/https://adventuregamers.com/news/view/19154 |archive-date=22 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2004, MC2-Micro\u00efds proceeded to close Micro\u00efds UK, while Micro\u00efds Italia spun off as Blue Label Entertainment.<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 154\" /> Micro\u00efds Canada was sold off to [[Ubisoft]] in March 2005, with the studio's 50 employees integrated into Ubisoft's own [[Ubisoft Montreal]] studio.<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 154\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/news040305ubisoftmicroids |title=Ubisoft buys Microids Canada |author=GamesIndustry International |date=4 March 2005 |website=[[Eurogamer]] |access-date=22 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191022223811/https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/news040305ubisoftmicroids |archive-date=22 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Later that year, Grassiano left MC2-Micro\u00efds due to internal disagreements. He was succeeded by Index+ founder Emmanuel Olivier, who was named [[chief executive officer]] (CEO).<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 154\" /> With this management change, MC2-Micro\u00efds shortened its name to just \"MC2\". This decision was reversed in November 2007, when it returned to the original \"Micro\u00efds\" name.<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 154\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://adventuregamers.com/news/view/20425 |title=MICRO\u00cfDS brand re-launched |first=Jack |last=Allin |date=28 November 2007 |website=[[Adventure Gamers]] |access-date=12 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190719233507/https://adventuregamers.com/news/view/20425 |archive-date=19 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2008, Micro\u00efds further acquired the assets and [[intellectual property]] of bankrupt publisher [[Cryo Interactive]].<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 154\" />\n\nIn 2009, the publisher Anuman Interactive, while in the process of being acquired by [[M\u00e9dia-Participations]], began looking for possible acquisitions of its own.<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 154\" /> That November, the company announced its intent to acquire Micro\u00efds.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamekult.com/actualite/anuman-s-offre-microids-81263.html |title=Anuman s'offre Micro\u00efds |language=fr |trans-title=Anuman to buy Micro\u00efds |author=hosteel |date=23 November 2009 |website=Gamekult |access-date=22 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191022224849/https://www.gamekult.com/actualite/anuman-s-offre-microids-81263.html |archive-date=22 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The acquisition was completed on 1 January 2010, after which Micro\u00efds continued operating as a [[Division (business)|division]] of Anuman. Alongside the acquisition, Olivier left the company. A sub-label for non-adventure games, Micro\u00efds Games for All, was launched the same year.<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 154\" /> In 2013, Grassiano joined Anuman and became the [[vice-president]] for Micro\u00efds.<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 154\" /> Additionally, an [[indie game]] label, Micro\u00efds Indie, was opened in September 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jeuxvideo.com/news/711167/microids-lance-son-label-microids-indie.htm |title=Micro\u00efds lance son label Micro\u00efds Indie |language=fr |trans-title=Micro\u00efds launches its label Micro\u00efds Indie |author=MalloDelic |date=13 September 2017 |website=[[Jeuxvideo.com]] |access-date=12 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018124615/http://www.jeuxvideo.com/news/711167/microids-lance-son-label-microids-indie.htm |archive-date=18 October 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> In July 2019, the Micro\u00efds label name was simplified to \"Microids\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.microids.com/microids-gets-a-makeover-discover-our-new-visual-identity/ |title=Microids gets a makeover: discover our new visual identity! |author=Team Microids |date=11 July 2019 |website=Microids |access-date=22 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191022163038/https://www.microids.com/microids-gets-a-makeover-discover-our-new-visual-identity/ |archive-date=22 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> That October, Microids announced that Anuman would be renamed \"Microids\", with Anuman CEO St\u00e9phane Longeard becoming the CEO of Microids, co-managing it with Grassiano. Microids also opened a Japanese office run by Martial Meyssignac and Yves Bl\u00e9haut, and strengthened the Microids Indie label with a dedicated team managed by Vincent Dondaine.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2019-10-21-anuman-interactive-becomes-microids-opens-japan-office |title=Anuman Interactive becomes Microids, opens Japan office |first=Rebekah |last=Valentine |date=21 October 2019 |website=[[GamesIndustry.biz]] |access-date=12 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021235346/https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2019-10-21-anuman-interactive-becomes-microids-opens-japan-office |archive-date=21 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Games ==\n{{Main|List of Micro\u00efds games}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://www.microids.com/}}\n\n[[Category:1985 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Paris]]\n[[Category:Entertainment Software Association]]\n[[Category:Video game companies established in 1984]]\n[[Category:Video game companies of France]]\n[[Category:Video game development companies]]\n[[Category:Video game publishers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Microids\n| logo = Microids-Logo.png\n| former_name = {{Unbulleted list|Micro\u00efds (1985\u20132003; 2007\u20132019)|MC2-Micro\u00efds (2003\u20132005)|MC2 (2005\u20132007)}}\n| type = [[Subsidiary]]\n| industry = [[Video game industry|Video games]]\n| founded = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1985}} in [[V\u00e9lizy-Villacoublay]], France\n| founder = Elliot Grassiano\n| hq_location_city = [[Paris]]\n| hq_location_country = France\n| key_people = {{Unbulleted list|St\u00e9phane Longeard ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])|Elliot Grassiano ([[Vice-president|VP]])}}\n| num_employees =\n| num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) -->\n| parent = {{Unbulleted list|Anuman Interactive (2010\u20132019)|[[M\u00e9dia-Participations]] (2019\u2013present)}}\n| website = {{URL|https://www.microids.com/|microids.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Microids''' (formerly '''Micro\u00efds''') is a French [[video game developer]] and [[Video game publisher|publisher]] based in [[Paris]]. Founded in 1985 by Elliot Grassiano, it attained early success with games published through [[Loriciel]] in France and other partners (including [[Activision]] and [[Broderbund]]) in international markets. Through expanding its staff and development teams, Micro\u00efds generated funds to expand from just development to [[Video game publishing|publishing]] and [[Wholesaling|distribution]] and opening international offices. The company merged with MC2 in 2003 to create MC2-Micro\u00efds, whereafter it acquired publishers Wanadoo Edition and [[Cryo Interactive]]. Grassiano left MC2-Micro\u00efds in 2005; under new management, MC2-Micro\u00efds was briefly renamed MC2 before returning to the old Micro\u00efds name. It was then acquired by Anuman Interactive in 2010, which itself was renamed Micro\u00efds (then simplified to Microids) in 2019.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Background and early years (1985\u20132003) ===\nMicro\u00efds was founded by Elliot Grassiano, a French [[Video game programmer|programmer]]. He was educated at the [[Lyc\u00e9e Louis-le-Grand]] school from 1972 to 1974 and later studied engineering, electronics, and computers at the [[\u00c9cole nationale sup\u00e9rieure d'arts et m\u00e9tiers]]. He started working as an engineer for the defence system company [[SAGEM]] in 1979. By the 1980s, Grassiano had become interested in [[telecommunications]], [[consumer electronics]], and video games. He acquired a [[Thomson MO5]] model [[home computer]], which he used to create his first game, ''Space Shuttle Simulator''. The game was published by [[Loriciel]] and released to both critical and commercial success. Subsequently, Grassiano quit his job to establish his own company. he formally founded Micro\u00efds in 1985, setting it up in [[V\u00e9lizy-Villacoublay]], a suburb of [[Paris]]. He was aided in these efforts by Loriciel's founders, Laurent Weill and Marc Bayle, as well as Patrick Le Nestour, another engineer. The name \"Micro\u00efds\" was a [[portmanteau]] of \"microinformatique\" and \"androids\". Within its first year of operation, the company grew to five people, with Grassiano in the managerial role.<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 154\">{{cite magazine |title=From the Archives: Micro\u00efds |first=David |last=Crookes |magazine=[[Retro Gamer]] |issue=154 |publisher=[[Imagine Publishing]] |date=21 April 2016 |pages=50\u201355}}</ref>\n\nInitially, Micro\u00efds set out to create consumer [[robotics]] projects before shifting its focus solely to video games. The first Micro\u00efds-developed game was ''Air Attack'', released by Loriciel for the Thomson MO5 to moderate commercial success. Early [[adventure game]]s developed by Micro\u00efds include ''Oceania'' (developed by Le Nestour and released in 1985 for the Thomson MO5 and [[Thomson TO7|TO7]]) and ''Les Pyramides D'Atlantys'' (developed by Luc Thibaud and released for the [[Amstrad CPC]] in 1986). ''Air Attack'' provided the groundwork for subsequent Micro\u00efds games, such as ''[[500 cc Grand Prix]]'' for the Amstrad CPC, which debuted in 1986. This game was the company's first breakthrough title, partially driven by the CPC's success in France. By way of a deal between Loriciel and [[Activision]], the game was also released in the UK, it was also released in the US, and it was later [[Porting|ported]] to other systems, such as the [[Atari ST]]. The American market appeared especially viable for Micro\u00efds, who believed that game sales would vastly outnumber the domestic ones. For this reason, it partnered with the American publisher [[Broderbund]] in 1987, which released several Micro\u00efds games in the country, partially under altered names. In return, Micro\u00efds managed sales of Broderbund's games, notably ''[[Prince of Persia (1989 video game)|Prince of Persia]]'' and ''[[Karateka (video game)|Karateka]]'' in France.<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 154\" />\n\nThroughout the 1990s, Micro\u00efds underwent expansion, increasing both staff count and development team sizes. Development operations were accelerated to output more games, leading to increased profits. Through the new-earned funds, the company commenced operations in both [[video game publishing]] and [[Wholesaling|distribution]] in 1995, and between then and 1997 opened three international subsidiaries: Micro\u00efds Italia in [[Milan]], Micro\u00efds UK in [[Milton Keynes]], and Micro\u00efds Canada in [[Montreal]]. By 1997, Micro\u00efds had 20 employees and a turnover of 20&nbsp;million [[French franc]]s. Both increased tenfold by 2002, and the Canadian studio alone house 105 of Micro\u00efds' 200 employees by 2003.<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 154\" />\n\n=== Mergers (2003\u2013present) ===\nIn 2003, Micro\u00efds merged with MC2, a French software company, with the amalgam assuming the name MC2-Micro\u00efds.<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 154\" /> In September that year, it acquired Wanadoo Edition, the games division of [[Wanadoo]], which itself had been created through a September 2000 merger between Index+ and France Telecom Multimedia in exchange, Wanadoo received a 12% stake in MC2-Micro\u00efds.<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 154\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://adventuregamers.com/news/view/19154 |title=Microids takes over Wanadoo's games division |first=Marek |last=Bronstring |date=2 October 2003 |website=[[Adventure Gamers]] |access-date=22 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191022223812/https://adventuregamers.com/news/view/19154 |archive-date=22 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2004, MC2-Micro\u00efds proceeded to close Micro\u00efds UK, while Micro\u00efds Italia spun off as Blue Label Entertainment.<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 154\" /> Micro\u00efds Canada was sold off to [[Ubisoft]] in March 2005, with the studio's 50 employees integrated into Ubisoft's own [[Ubisoft Montreal]] studio.<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 154\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/news040305ubisoftmicroids |title=Ubisoft buys Microids Canada |author=GamesIndustry International |date=4 March 2005 |website=[[Eurogamer]] |access-date=22 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191022223811/https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/news040305ubisoftmicroids |archive-date=22 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Later that year, Grassiano left MC2-Micro\u00efds due to internal disagreements. He was succeeded by Index+ founder Emmanuel Olivier, who was named [[chief executive officer]] (CEO).<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 154\" /> With this management change, MC2-Micro\u00efds shortened its name to just \"MC2\". This decision was reversed in November 2007, when it returned to the original \"Micro\u00efds\" name.<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 154\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://adventuregamers.com/news/view/20425 |title=MICRO\u00cfDS brand re-launched |first=Jack |last=Allin |date=28 November 2007 |website=[[Adventure Gamers]] |access-date=12 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190719233507/https://adventuregamers.com/news/view/20425 |archive-date=19 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2008, Micro\u00efds further acquired the assets and [[intellectual property]] of bankrupt publisher [[Cryo Interactive]].<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 154\" />\n\nIn 2009, the publisher Anuman Interactive, while in the process of being acquired by [[M\u00e9dia-Participations]], began looking for possible acquisitions of its own.<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 154\" /> That November, the company announced its intent to acquire Micro\u00efds.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamekult.com/actualite/anuman-s-offre-microids-81263.html |title=Anuman s'offre Micro\u00efds |language=fr |trans-title=Anuman to buy Micro\u00efds |author=hosteel |date=23 November 2009 |website=Gamekult |access-date=22 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191022224849/https://www.gamekult.com/actualite/anuman-s-offre-microids-81263.html |archive-date=22 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The acquisition was completed on 1 January 2010, after which Micro\u00efds continued operating as a [[Division (business)|division]] of Anuman. Alongside the acquisition, Olivier left the company. A sub-label for non-adventure games, Micro\u00efds Games for All, was launched the same year.<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 154\" /> In 2013, Grassiano joined Anuman and became the [[vice-president]] for Micro\u00efds.<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 154\" /> Additionally, an [[indie game]] label, Micro\u00efds Indie, was opened in September 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jeuxvideo.com/news/711167/microids-lance-son-label-microids-indie.htm |title=Micro\u00efds lance son label Micro\u00efds Indie |language=fr |trans-title=Micro\u00efds launches its label Micro\u00efds Indie |author=MalloDelic |date=13 September 2017 |website=[[Jeuxvideo.com]] |access-date=12 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018124615/http://www.jeuxvideo.com/news/711167/microids-lance-son-label-microids-indie.htm |archive-date=18 October 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> In July 2019, the Micro\u00efds label name was simplified to \"Microids\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.microids.com/microids-gets-a-makeover-discover-our-new-visual-identity/ |title=Microids gets a makeover: discover our new visual identity! |author=Team Microids |date=11 July 2019 |website=Microids |access-date=22 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191022163038/https://www.microids.com/microids-gets-a-makeover-discover-our-new-visual-identity/ |archive-date=22 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> That October, Microids announced that Anuman would be renamed \"Microids\", with Anuman CEO St\u00e9phane Longeard becoming the CEO of Microids, co-managing it with Grassiano. Microids also opened a Japanese office run by Martial Meyssignac and Yves Bl\u00e9haut, and strengthened the Microids Indie label with a dedicated team managed by Vincent Dondaine.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2019-10-21-anuman-interactive-becomes-microids-opens-japan-office |title=Anuman Interactive becomes Microids, opens Japan office |first=Rebekah |last=Valentine |date=21 October 2019 |website=[[GamesIndustry.biz]] |access-date=12 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021235346/https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2019-10-21-anuman-interactive-becomes-microids-opens-japan-office |archive-date=21 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Games ==\n{{Main|List of Micro\u00efds games}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://www.microids.com/}}\n\n[[Category:1985 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Paris]]\n[[Category:Entertainment Software Association]]\n[[Category:Video game companies established in 1984]]\n[[Category:Video game companies of France]]\n[[Category:Video game development companies]]\n[[Category:Video game publishers]]\n", "name_user": "IceWelder", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground and early years (1985\u20132003)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microids"}
{"title_page": "Arminius", "text_new": "{{short description|Chieftain of the Germanic Cherusci tribe}}\n{{About|the Germanic chieftain|other uses|Arminius (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name               = Arminius\n| office              = Prince and Chieftain of the Cherusci tribe\n| image              = Hermannsdenkmal statue.jpg\n| caption            = [[Hermannsdenkmal]] memorial\n| reign              =\n| coronation         =\n| full name          =\n| native_lang1       =\n| native_lang1_name1 = Armin, Hermann\n| birth_date         = 18/17 BC\n| birth_place        = [[Germania]]\n| death_date         = 21 AD (aged 37\u201338)\n| death_place        = [[Germania]]\n| burial_date        =\n| burial_place       = <!-- <br /> {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| predecessor        = [[Segimer]]\n| successor          = [[Italicus]]\n| spouse             = [[Thusnelda]]\n| issue              = [[Thumelicus]]\n| royal house        =\n| dynasty            =\n| father             = [[Segimer]]\n| mother             =\n| religion           = [[Germanic religion (aboriginal)|Germanic]]\n| signature          =\n}}\n\n'''Arminius''' ({{lang-de|Hermann}}; 18/17 BC \u2013 AD 21) was a chieftain of the [[Germanic peoples|Germanic]] [[Cherusci]] tribe who is best known for commanding an alliance of Germanic tribes at the [[Battle of the Teutoburg Forest]] in AD 9, in which three [[Roman legion]]s were destroyed. His victory at Teutoburg Forest would precipitate the [[Roman Empire]]'s permanent strategic withdrawal from [[Magna Germania]], and made a major contribution to the eventual [[Fall of the Western Roman Empire|fall]] of the [[Western Roman Empire]] several centuries later.<ref>{{cite book|author=Dr. Aaron Ralby|title=Atlas of Military History|url=https://archive.org/details/atlasofworldmili0000ralb|url-access=registration|year=2013|publisher=Parragon|isbn=978-1-4723-0963-1|page=[https://archive.org/details/atlasofworldmili0000ralb/page/241 241]|chapter=The Roman Legion: Refining Military Organization}}</ref> Modern historians have regarded Arminius' victory as Rome's greatest defeat.<ref name=\"Murdoch\">{{harvnb|Murdoch|2012|p=}}</ref> As it prevented the [[Romanization (cultural)|Romanization]] of the Germanic peoples, it has also been considered one of the most decisive battles in history,<ref name=\"Tucker\">{{harvnb|Tucker|2010|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=wHpVn68GCogC&pg=PA75 75]}}</ref><ref name=\"Cawthorne\">{{harvnb|Cawthorne|2012|p=}}</ref><ref name=\"Davis\">{{harvnb|Davis|1999|p=[https://books.google.com/books?hl=no&id=nv73QlQs9ocC&pg=PA68 68]}}</ref><ref name=\"Creasy\">{{harvnb|Creasy|2007|p=104}}</ref> and a turning point in [[History of the world|world history]].<ref name=\"Spectator\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.spectator.co.uk/books/20823/how-the-eagles-were-tamed/ |title=How the eagles were tamed |date=March 27, 2004 |magazine=[[The Spectator]] |accessdate=January 16, 2015 |quote=[[Theodor Mommsen|Mommsen]] referred to the Battle of the Teutoburg forest as a turning-point in world history.}}</ref> \n\nBorn a prince of the Cherusci tribe, Arminius was made a hostage of the Roman Empire as a child. Raised in [[Rome]], he was drafted into the [[Military of ancient Rome|Roman military]] at an early age, during which he was granted [[Roman citizenship]] and became a [[Equites|Roman knight]]. After serving with distinction in the [[Bellum Batonianum|Great Illyrian Revolt]], he was sent to [[Germania]] to aid the local governor [[Publius Quinctilius Varus]] in completing the Roman conquest of the Germanic tribes. While in this capacity, Arminius secretly plotted a Germanic revolt against Roman rule, which culminated in the ambush and destruction of three Roman legions in the Teutoburg Forest.\n\nIn the aftermath of the battle, Arminius fought retaliatory invasions by the Roman general [[Germanicus]] in the battles of [[Battle at Pontes Longi|Pontes Longi]], [[Battle of Idistaviso|Idistaviso]], and the [[Battle of the Angrivarian Wall|Angrivarian Wall]], and deposed a rival, the [[Marcomanni]] king [[Maroboduus]]. Germanic nobles, afraid of Arminius' growing power, assassinated him in AD 21. He was remembered in [[Saga|Germanic legends]] for generations afterwards.<ref name=\"Annals.02.88\"/> The Roman historian [[Tacitus]] designated Arminius as the liberator of the Germanic tribes and commended him for having fought the Roman Empire to a standstill at the peak of its power.<ref name=\"Annals.02.88\">[[Tacitus]]. [[wikisource:The Annals (Tacitus)/Book 2#63|The Annals.2.88]]. \"Assuredly he was the deliverer of Germany, one too who had defied Rome, not in her early rise, as other kings and generals, but in the height of her empire's glory, had fought, indeed, indecisive battles, yet in war remained unconquered. He completed thirty-seven years of life, twelve years of power, and he is still a theme of song among barbarous nations, though to Greek historians, who admire only their own achievements, he is unknown, and to Romans not as famous as he should be, while we extol the past and are indifferent to our own times.\"</ref>  \n\nDuring the [[unification of Germany]] in the 19th century, Arminius was hailed by [[German nationalism|German nationalists]] as a symbol of German unity and freedom.<ref name=\"Spiegel\">{{cite web |url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/battle-of-the-teutoburg-forest-germany-recalls-myth-that-created-the-nation-a-644913.html |title= Battle of the Teutoburg Forest: Germany Recalls Myth That Created the Nation |last1=Crossland |first1=David |date=August 28, 2009 |website=[[Spiegel Online|Spiegel Online International]] |publisher=[[Der Spiegel]] |accessdate=January 16, 2015}}</ref> Following [[World War II]], however, Arminius was [[Memory hole|omitted]] from German textbooks due to his association with militaristic nationalism, and many modern Germans are unaware of his story; the 2,000th anniversary of his victory at the Teutoburg Forest was only lightly commemorated in Germany.<ref name=\"Spiegel\"/>\n\n==Name==\n[[File:ArminiusbyGeorgeSStuart.jpg|thumb|left|200px|No known portrait image of Arminius exists from life. This likeness was created by artist and historian George S. Stuart from physical descriptions mentioned in historical records.]]\nThe [[etymology]] of the Latin name ''Arminius'' is unknown; confusion is further created by contemporary scholars who alternately referred to him as ''Armenus''.<ref name=\"MurdochEtymology\">{{cite book |last1=Murdoch |first1=Adrian |title=Rome's Greatest Defeat: Massacre in the Teutoburg Forest |date=2009 |publisher=The History Press |isbn=0750940166 |page=84}}</ref> [[Marcus Velleius Paterculus]], in his ''Historiae'', mentions him as \"Arminius, the son of Sigimer, a prince of [the German] nation\" and states he \"attained the dignity of [[Equites|equestrian rank]]\".<ref>{{cite book|url=http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Velleius_Paterculus/2D*.html|title=The Roman History|author=C. Velleius Paterculus|publisher=Loeb Classical Library|date=1924|page=118}}</ref> Due to [[Roman naming conventions#Foreign names|Roman naming conventions]] of the time, it is likely ''Arminius'' is an adopted name granted to him upon citizenship, or otherwise not his Cheruscan name; although the theory that the name alludes to prior service on the [[Lesser Armenia#Roman\u2013Persian_wars|eastern frontier of the Roman empire]] is now largely discredited.<ref name=\"MurdochEtymology\" />\n\nThe German translation of ''Arminius'' as ''Hermann'' dates from the 16th century, possibly first by [[Martin Luther]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Arminius into Hermann: History into Legend|author=Herbert W. Benario|journal=Greece and Rome|volume=51|issue=1|date=April 2004|pages=83\u201394|doi= 10.1093/gr/51.1.83}}</ref> In German, Arminius is traditionally known as ''Hermann der Cherusker'' (\"Hermann the Cheruscan\") or ''Hermann der Cheruskerf\u00fcrst'' (\"Hermann the Cheruscan Prince\"). Hermann etymologically means \"Man of War\", coming from the [[Old High German]] ''heri'' \"war\" and ''man'' \"man\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=F\u00f6rstemann|first1=Ernst Wilhelm|title=Altdeutsches Namenbuch|date=1900|publisher=Nabu Press|isbn=9781270714996|language=German}}</ref><ref>http://www.vorname.com/name,Hermann.html</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:Stammbaum ADBSegest.jpg|right|400px|thumb|Relatives of Arminius]]\nBorn in 18 or 17 BC in [[Germania]], Arminius was the son of the Cheruscan chief [[Segimerus]] (German: ''Segimer''; Proto-Germanic: ''Sigimariz''; Old English: ''Sigemaer''). He lived in Rome as a hostage during his youth, where he learned to speak [[Latin]] and trained as a Roman military commander alongside his younger brother [[Flavus (son of Segimerus)|Flavus]]. He served in the Roman army between AD 1 and 6, and received a military education as well as [[Roman citizenship]] and the status of [[equite]] before returning to Germania.<ref name=\"Durschmied\">{{harvnb|Durschmied|2013|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=ESY980GKv3cC&pg=PA1759 p. 1759]}}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Arminius|encyclopedia=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Ultimate Reference Suite]]|year=2014|publisher=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc.|Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]|location=Chicago}}</ref> These experiences gave him knowledge of Roman politics and military tactics, which allowed him to successfully anticipate enemy battle maneuvers during his later campaigns against the Roman army.\n\n===Battle of the Teutoburg Forest===\n{{Main article|Battle of the Teutoburg Forest}}\n[[File:Magna Germania before the battle of the Teutoburg Forest.png|right|thumb|Magna Germania in AD 9. The yellow legend represents the areas controlled by the [[Roman Republic]] in 31 BC, the shades of green represent gradually conquered territories under the reign of [[Augustus]], and pink areas on the map represent tributary tribes.]]\nAround the year AD 4, Arminius assumed command of a Cheruscan detachment of Roman auxiliary forces, probably while fighting in the [[Pannonian]] wars on the [[Balkan peninsula]]. He returned to northern Germania in AD 7 or 8, where the Roman Empire had established secure control of the territories just east of the [[Rhine]], along the [[Lippe]] and [[Main (river)|Main]] rivers, and was now seeking to extend its hegemony eastward to the [[Weser]] and [[Elbe]] rivers, under [[Publius Quinctilius Varus]], a high-ranking administrative official appointed by [[Augustus]] as governor. Arminius began plotting to unite various Germanic tribes in order to thwart Roman efforts to incorporate their lands into the empire. This proved a difficult task, as the tribes were strongly independent and many were traditionally enemies of each other.\n\nBetween AD 6 and 9, the Romans were forced to move eight of the eleven legions present in Germania east of the Rhine to crush a [[Great Illyrian Revolt|rebellion]] in the [[Balkans]],<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.livius.org/le-lh/legio/v_alaudae.html | date = September 2010 | title = Legio V Alaudae | publisher = www.livius.org}}</ref> leaving Varus with only three legions to face the Germans. An additional two legions, under the command of [[Lucius Nonius Asprenas (suffect consul AD 6)|Lucius Nonius Asprenas]], were stationed in [[Moguntiacum]].<ref>Syme, pg. 60</ref> Arminius saw this as the perfect opportunity to defeat Varus.<ref>Velleius Paterculus, ''Compendium of Roman History'' 2, 109, 5; [[Cassius Dio]], ''Roman History'' 55, 28, 6\u20137</ref>\n\n[[File:Otto Albert Koch Varusschlacht 1909.jpg|left|thumb|''Varusschlacht'', Otto Albert Koch (1909)]]\nIn the autumn of AD 9, the 25-year-old Arminius brought to Varus a false report of rebellion in northern Germany. He persuaded Varus to divert the three legions under his command (composed of the [[Legio XVII|17th]], [[Legio XVIII|18th]], and [[Legio XIX|19th]] [[Roman legion|legions]], plus three [[cavalry]] detachments and six [[cohort (military unit)|cohorts]] of auxiliaries), which were at the time marching to winter quarters, to suppress the rebellion. Varus and his legions marched right into the trap that Arminius had set for them near [[Kalkriese]]. Arminius' tribe, the [[Cherusci]], and their allies the [[Marsi (Germanic)|Marsi]], [[Chatti]], [[Bructeri]], [[Chauci]], and [[Sicambri]] (five out of at least fifty Germanic tribes at the time)<ref name=\"Spiegel\"/> ambushed and annihilated Varus' entire army, totaling over 20,000 men, as it marched along a narrow road through a dense forest. Recent archaeological finds show the long-debated location of the three-day battle was almost certainly near Kalkriese Hill, about 20&nbsp;km north of present-day [[Osnabr\u00fcck]]. When defeat was certain, Varus committed suicide by falling on his sword. The battle was one of the most devastating defeats Rome suffered in its history. Arminius' success in destroying three entire legions and driving the Romans out of Germany marked a high point of Germanic power for centuries. Roman attempts to reconquer Germania failed, although they did eventually manage to break Arminius' carefully coordinated alliance.\n\n===Roman retaliation, inter-tribal conflicts, and death===\n[[File:Blick-\u00fcber-den-Teutoburger-Wald1.jpg|thumb|right|300px|View over the [[Teutoburg Forest]]]]\nAfter the battle, the Germans quickly annihilated every trace of Roman presence east of the Rhine. Roman settlements such as the [[Waldgirmes Forum]] were abandoned. The vastly outnumbered Roman garrison of Aliso (present-day [[Haltern am See]]), under the command of the prefect Lucius Cedicius, inflicted heavy losses on the Germans before retreating into [[Gaul]], resisting long enough for Lucius Nonius Asprenas to organize the Roman defense on the Rhine and [[Tiberius]] to arrive with a new army. This prevented Arminius from crossing the Rhine and invading Gaul.<ref>Velleius Paterculus, Compendium of Roman History II, 120, 4; Cassius Dio, Roman History LVI, 22, 2a-2b</ref>\n\nBetween AD 14 and 16, [[Germanicus]] led punitive operations into Germany, fighting Arminius to a draw in the [[Battle at Pontes Longi]] and twice defeating him (according to Tacitus): first in the [[Battle of Idistaviso]] and later at the [[Battle of the Angrivarian Wall]]. In AD 15, Roman troops managed to recapture one of the three [[aquila (Roman)|legionary eagles]] lost in the Battle of the Teutoburg Forest. In AD 16, a second eagle was retrieved.<ref>Tac. ''Ann''. 1.60.4, 2.25.2</ref> Tiberius denied the request of Germanicus to launch an additional campaign for AD 17, however, having decided the frontier with Germania would stand at the Rhine river. Instead, he offered Germanicus the honor of a triumph for his two victories. The third Roman eagle was recovered in AD 41 by Publius Gabinius, under the emperor [[Claudius]].<ref>Dio 60.8.7.</ref> Arminius also faced opposition from his father-in-law and other pro-Roman Germanic leaders.<ref>Tac. ''Ann''. 1.54\u201359.</ref> His brother [[Flavus (son of Segimerus)|Flavus]], who had been raised alongside him in Rome, remained loyal to the Roman Empire and fought under Germanicus against Arminius at the Battle of Idistaviso. With the end of the Roman threat, a war broke out between Arminius and [[Maroboduus|Marbod]], king of the [[Marcomanni]]. It ended with Marbod fleeing to [[Ravenna]] and Roman protection, but Arminius failed to break into the \"natural fortification\" of [[Bohemia]], and the war ended in stalemate.\n\nIn AD 19, Germanicus died in [[Antioch]] under circumstances which led many to believe he had been poisoned by his opponents. Arminius died two years later, in AD 21, murdered by opponents within his own tribe who felt that he was becoming too powerful.<ref name=\"tacit\">Tacitus, The Annals [[s:The Annals (Tacitus)/Book 2#88|2.88]]</ref><ref>[[Tacitus]], ''Annals'' 2.22 ff.; [[Suetonius]], ''Caligula'' 1.4; Dio 57.18.1; on Arminius' assassination, Tac. ''Ann''. 2.88;</ref> Tiberius allegedly had refused an earlier offer from a Chatti nobleman to poison Arminius: \"It was not by secret treachery but openly and by arms that the people of Rome avenged themselves on their enemies.\"<ref>Tac. ''Ann''. 2.87\u201388.</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nArminius married a princess named [[Thusnelda]], whose name is preserved only by [[Strabo]]. She was captured by the Romans while pregnant, so her son [[Thumelicus]] grew up in Roman captivity. [[Tacitus]] describes him as having an unusual story, which the historian promises to tell, but this part of Tacitus' writings has since been lost.\n\nArminius' victory against the Roman legions in the Teutoburg Forest had a far-reaching effect on the subsequent history of both the ancient [[Germanic peoples]] and on the Roman Empire. The Romans made no further concerted efforts to conquer and permanently hold Germania beyond the Rhine and the [[Agri Decumates]]. Numerous modern historians have regarded Arminius' victory as \"Rome's greatest defeat\"<ref name=\"Murdoch\"/> and one of the most decisive battles in history.<ref name=\"Tucker\"/><ref name=\"Cawthorne\"/><ref name=\"Davis\"/><ref name=\"Creasy\"/><ref name=\"Spectator\"/><ref name=\"Durschmied\"/>\n\n===Rome===\n[[File:Arminius pushkin.jpg|right|thumb|This Roman sculpture of a young man is sometimes identified as Arminius<ref name=britannica>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Arminius|title=Arminius|work=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Thusnelda Loggia dei Lanzi 2005 09 13.jpg|thumb|upright=0.7|Thusnelda statue in [[Loggia dei Lanzi]], Florence]]\nIn the accounts of his Roman enemies, Arminius is highly regarded for his military leadership and as a defender of the liberty of his people. Based on these records, the story of Arminius was revived in the 16th century with the recovery of the histories of [[Tacitus]], who wrote in his ''Annales II, 88'':\n\n{{quote|text=Arminius, without doubt Germania's liberator, who challenged the Roman people not in its beginnings like other kings and leaders, but in the peak of its empire; in battles with changing success, undefeated in the war.<ref>{{cite book|title=Arminius the Liberator: Myth and Ideology|first=Martin M.|last=Winkler|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|date=2016|isbn=9780190252915|page=30}}</ref>}}\n\nArminius was not the only reason for Rome's change of policy towards Germania. Politics also played a factor; emperors found they could rarely trust a large army to a potential rival, though Augustus had enough loyal family members to wage his wars. Also, Augustus, in his 40-year reign, had annexed many territories still at the beginning of the process of Romanization. Tiberius, who succeeded Augustus in AD 14, decided that Germania was a far less developed land, possessing few villages and only a small food surplus, and therefore was not currently important to Rome. Conquering Germania would require a commitment too burdensome for the imperial finances and an excessive expenditure of military force.\n\nModern scholars have pointed out that the [[Rhine]] was a more practical boundary for the Roman Empire than any other river in Germania. Armies on the Rhine could be supplied from the [[Mediterranean Sea]] via the [[Rh\u00f4ne]], [[Sa\u00f4ne]], and [[Moselle (river)|Mosel]], with only a brief area of portage. Armies on the [[Elbe]], however, would had to have been supplied by extensive overland routes or by ships travelling the hazardous Atlantic. Economically, the Rhine already had towns and sizable villages at the time of the Gallic conquest. The Rhine was significantly more accessible from Rome and better equipped to supply sizable garrisons than the regions beyond.<ref>Peter Heather (2006). ''The Fall of the Roman Empire: A New History of Rome and the Barbarians''.</ref>\n\nRome chose no longer to rule directly in Germania east of the [[Rhine]] and north of the [[Danube]], instead preferring to exert indirect influence by appointing [[client king]]s, which was cheaper than military campaigns. [[Italicus]], nephew of Arminius, was appointed king of the Cherusci; [[Vangio and Sido]] became [[vassal]] princes of the powerful [[Suebi]], etc.<ref>[[Annals (Tacitus)|Tacitus]], Book 12 [verse 27 to 31]</ref> When indirect methods proved insufficient to control the Germanic tribes beyond the Rhine, Roman emperors occasionally led devastating punitive campaigns deep into Germania. One of them, led by the Roman emperor [[Maximinus Thrax]], resulted in a Roman victory in AD 235 at the [[Battle at the Harzhorn]] Hill,<ref>Historia Augusta, ''The Two Maximini'' 12:1\u20134; Herodian, ''Roman History'', Book 7:2:3</ref> located in the modern German state of [[Lower Saxony]], east of the [[Weser]] river, between the towns of [[Kalefeld]] and [[Bad Gandersheim]].\n\n===Old Germanic sagas===\nIn the early 19th century, attempts were made to show that the story of Arminius and his victory may have lived on in the [[Old Norse]] [[sagas]],<ref>{{cite journal|title=Ueber den Ursprung der Siegfriedsage|author=A. Giesebrecht|journal=Germania|issue=2|year=1837|url=https://archive.org/details/UeberDenUrsprungDerSiegfriedsage/}}</ref> in the form of the dragon slayer [[Sigurd]] of the [[V\u00f6lsunga saga]] and the [[Nibelungenlied]]. An Icelandic account<ref>{{cite journal|title= Nikulas Bergsson, Arnamagn\u00e6an Collection manuscript 194, 8yo |author=unknown | year=1387}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title= Altnordische Kosmographie: Studien und Quellen zu Weltbild und Weltbeschreibung in Norwegen und in Island vom 12. bis zum 14. Jahrhundert |author= Simek, R. |journal= Berlin/New York | year=1990}}</ref>\nstates that Sigurd \"slew the dragon\" in the Gnitaheidr\u2014today the suburb Knetterheide of the city of [[Bad Salzuflen]], located at a strategic site on the [[Werre]] river which could very well have been the point of departure of Varus' legions on their way to their doom in the Teutoburg Forest. One of the foremost Scandinavian scholars of the 19th century, [[Gu\u00f0brandur Vigf\u00fasson]],<ref>{{cite book|title=Grimm centenary; Sigfred-Arminivs, and other papers\n|author= G. Vigfusson, F. York Powell|publisher=Oxford Clarendon Press|year=1886|url=https://archive.org/details/grimmcentenarysi00gudb}}</ref> identified Sigurd as Arminius. This educated guess was also picked up by [[Otto H\u00f6fler]], who was a prominent [[National Socialist]] academic during World War II.<ref>O. H\u00f6fler, \"Siegfried Arminius und die Symbolik,\"  ''Heidelberg'' (1961), 60\u201364, and also in ''Siegfried, Arminius und der Nibelungenhort'' (Vienna 1978); F.G. Gentry, W. McConnell, W. Wunderlich (eds.), ''The Nibelungen Tradition. An Encyclopedia'' (New York\u2013London 2002), article \"Sigurd\".</ref>\n\n===German nationalism===\nDuring the [[unification of Germany]] in the 19th century, Arminius was hailed as a symbol of German unity and freedom.<ref name=\"Spiegel\"/> In Germany, the name ''Arminius'' was interpreted as reflecting the name ''Hermann'' by [[Martin Luther]], who saw Arminius as a symbol of the German people and their fight against Rome.<ref>{{cite journal|title=German Pagan Antiquity in Lutheran Historical Thought|author=W. Bradford Smith|journal=The Journal of the Historical Society|volume=4|issue=3|year=2004|pages=351\u201374 | doi = 10.1111/j.1529-921X.2004.00104.x}}</ref> ''Hermann der Cheruskerf\u00fcrst'' became an emblem of the revival of [[German nationalism]] fueled by the [[Napoleonic Wars]] in the 19th century.<ref name=\"Klein/K\u00e4ppel\">Dorothea Klein (ed.), Lutz K\u00e4ppel (ed.): ''Das diskursive Erbe Europas: Antike und Antikerezeption''. Peter Lang, 2008, {{ISBN|9783631560136}},  [https://books.google.com/books?id=yvfqcAjU9wsC&pg=PA329 p. 329]</ref>\n\n[[File:Gehrts Armin verabschiedet sich von Thusnelda 1884.jpg|thumb|Arminius says goodbye to [[Thusnelda]], [[Johannes Gehrts]] (1884)]]\nIn 1808, [[Heinrich von Kleist]] wrote the play ''[[Die Hermannsschlacht (Kleist)|Die Hermannsschlacht]]'',<ref>Heinrich von Kleist: Die Herrmannsschlacht. Ein Drama [1808] (Frankfurt am Main and Basel: Stroemfeld-Roter Stern, 2001).</ref> but with Napoleon's [[Battle of Wagram|victory at Wagram]] it remained in manuscript, being published in 1821 and not staged until 1860. The play has been revived repeatedly at moments propitious for raw expressions of [[National Romanticism]] and was especially popular during the [[Third Reich]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia| encyclopedia=The Literary Encyclopedia | title=Die Hermannsschlacht | first=William C | last=Reeve | year=2004 | url= http://www.litencyc.com/php/sworks.php?rec=true&UID=13117 | publisher=The Literary Dictionary Company | accessdate=2006-09-06}}</ref>\n\nIn 1838, construction was started on a massive statue of Arminius, known as the ''[[Hermannsdenkmal]]'', on a hill near [[Detmold]] in the Teutoburg Forest; it was finally completed and dedicated during the early years of the Second [[German Empire]] in the wake of the German victory over France in the [[Franco-Prussian War]] of 1870\u20131871. The monument has been a major tourist attraction ever since, as has the [[Hermann Heights Monument]], a similar statue erected in [[New Ulm, Minnesota]] in the United States in 1897. The Hermann Heights monument was erected by the [[Sons of Hermann]], a fraternal organization formed by [[German American]]s in New York City in 1840 that flourished during the 19th century in American cities with large populations of German origin. [[Hermann, Missouri]], a town on the Missouri River founded in the 1830s and incorporated in 1845, was also named for Arminius.\n\nFollowing the rise of [[Nazi Germany]], fueled by aggressive German nationalism, and its subsequent defeat in [[World War II]], Arminius became a lesser-known figure among [[West Germany|West Germans]] and many schools shunned away from teaching his story in any detail due to its previous association with nationalism.<ref name=\"Spiegel\"/> There was, however, a somewhat different perception in [[East Germany]]. In East Germany, Arminius, based on a [[Marxism|Marxist]] reading of history, came to be seen as a revolutionary figure of sorts, leading German tribes in a fight against the Roman slaveholder society (''Sklavenhaltergesellschaft''). In the context of the [[Cold War]], Arminius was interpreted as symbolic of [[socialism]], with Rome being a symbol of the [[capitalism|capitalist]] United States as an oppressive empire.<ref name=zeit> Tillmann Bendikowski: [http://www.zeit.de/2008/45/DOS-varus-schlacht ''Deutsche Geschichte \u2013 Mythos einer Schlacht'']. Zeit Online, 2008-11-04 (German)</ref>\n\nThe 2,000-year anniversary of the Battle of the Teutoburg Forest, in 2009, was celebrated with restraint in Germany, avoiding \"flag-waving festivals\" and other gestures that might be interpreted as nationalism.<ref name=\"Spiegel\"/> According to ''[[Der Spiegel]]'': \"The old nationalism has been replaced by an easy-going [[patriotism]] that mainly manifests itself at sporting events like the soccer<!-- Do not change this to \"football\". This is a direct quote. --> [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]].\"<ref name=\"Spiegel\"/> The German Bundesliga football club [[DSC Arminia Bielefeld]] is named after Arminius. The 2,000-year anniversary of the battle was also celebrated in New Ulm, Minnesota without restraint. There were mock battles between Romans and club-wielding barbarians and also a lecture series in an auditorium.<ref>[https://www.twincities.com/2009/09/20/new-ulm-celebrates-2000th-anniversary-of-battle/ New Ulm celebrates 2,000th anniversary of battle]</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n{{In popular culture|date=July 2017}}\n;Music\n* ''[[Arminio (Biber)|Arminio]]'' is a 1692 opera about Arminius by the Bohemian-Austrian composer [[Heinrich Ignaz Franz Biber]].\n* ''[[Arminio]]'' is a 1736 opera about Arminius by [[George Frideric Handel]].\n* ''[[Arminius (Bruch)|Arminius]]'' is an 1877 oratorio about Arminius by the German composer [[Max Bruch]].\n* ''Schlammschlacht'' is a 2015 spoken word song about Arminius and the [[Battle of the Teutoburg Forest]] by the Danish band [[Heilung]].\n;Historical novels\n* At the end of [[G. A. Henty]]'s 1887 ''The Young Carthaginan'' about the [[Second Punic War]], the main fictional character, Malchus, a cousin of [[Hannibal]], decides to settle with the tribes north of the Alps and becomes an ancestor of Arminius.\n* In the Czech novel ''[[Zlomen\u00fd Me\u010d]]'' (\"Broken sword\") by [[Eduard \u0160torch]], published in 1932, Arminius challenges the [[Marcomanni]] king [[Marobodus]] for the leadership of the Germanic tribes. The novel mistakenly shows the Celtic tribesmen as being Slavs to support the rising Slavonic identification of the nationalistic Czechs.\n* [[Robert Graves]]' fictional autobiography ''[[I, Claudius]]'' (1934) includes a description of Arminius' campaigns, where he is called \"Hermann\"; he is killed by members of his own family when he tries to \"issue orders like a king\".\n* Arminius is a character in ''[[Give Me Back My Legions!]]'', a 2009 historical novel by [[Harry Turtledove]] that retells the story of the Battle of the Teutoburg Forest.\n;Film\n* In the 2016 American docudrama ''[[Barbarians Rising]]'', Arminius is played by [[Tom Hopper]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Ancient Germanic culture}}\n* [[Ariovistus]]\n* [[Bato (Breucian chieftain)]]\n* [[Bato (Daesitiate chieftain)]]\n* [[Boudica]]\n* [[Divico]]\n* [[Flavus (son of Segimerus)|Flavus]]\n* [[Gaius Julius Civilis]]\n* [[Teutobod]]\n* [[Vercingetorix]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book |last=Cawthorne |first=Nigel |authorlink=Nigel Cawthorne |date=July 24, 2012 |title=Battles That Changed History: An Encyclopedia of World Conflict |url=https://books.google.com/?id=wHpVn68GCogC&pg=PA75 |location= |publisher=Arcturus Publishing |pages=75\u201377 |isbn=978-1848589544 |accessdate= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Davis |first=Paul K. |authorlink=Paul K. Davis (historian) |date=1999 |title=100 Decisive Battles: From Ancient Times to the Present |url=https://books.google.no/books?id=nv73QlQs9ocC |location= |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |pages=68\u201371 |isbn=0195143663 |accessdate= |ref=harv}}\n* Andreas D\u00f6rner, ''Politischer Mythos und symbolische Politik. Der Hermannmythos: Zur Entstehung des Nationalbewu\u00dftseins der Deutschen'' (Reinbek: Rowohlt, 1996).\n* {{cite book |last=Durschmied |first=Erik |authorlink=Erik Durschmied |date=April 13, 2013 |title=The Weather Factor: How Nature Has Changed History |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ESY980GKv3cC&pg=PA1751 |location= |publisher=[[Hachette (publisher)|Hachette UK]] |pages=1751\u201370|isbn=978-1444769654 |accessdate= |ref=harv}}\n* Gesa von Essen, ''Hermannsschlachten. Germanen- und R\u00f6merbilder in der Literatur des 18. und 19. Jahrhunderts'' (G\u00f6ttingen: Wallstein, 1998).\n* Richard Kuehnemund, ''Arminius or the Rise of a National Symbol in Literature. From Hutten to Grabbe'' (New York: AMS Press, 1966).\n* Herfried M\u00fcnkler / Hans Gr\u00fcnberger: Arminius/ Hermann als nationales Symbol im Diskurs der deutschen Humanisten 1500\u20131570, In: Herfried M\u00fcnkler / Hans Gr\u00fcnberger / Kathrin Mayer, ''Nationenbildung. Die Nationalisierung Europas im Diskurs humanistischer Intellektueller. Italien und Deutschland'' (Berlin: Akademie, 1998), pp.&nbsp;263\u2013308.\n* {{cite book |last=Murdoch |first=Adrian |date=1 December 2012 |title=Rome's Greatest Defeat: Massacre in the Teutoburg Forest |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Pao7AwAAQBAJ |location= |publisher=[[The History Press]] |page= |isbn=978-0752494555 |accessdate=|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Tucker |first=Spencer |authorlink=Spencer C. Tucker |date=2010 |title=Battles That Changed History: An Encyclopedia of World Conflict |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wHpVn68GCogC |location= |publisher=[[ABC-CLIO]] |page= |isbn=978-1598844290 |accessdate= |ref=harv}}\n* Martina Wagner-Egelhaaf (Ed.), ''Hermanns Schlachten. Zur Literaturgeschichte eines nationalen Mythos'' (Bielefeld: Aisthesis, 2008).\n* Reinhard Wolters, ''Die Schlacht im Teutoburger Wald: Arminius, Varus und das roemische Germanien'' (M\u00fcnchen: Verlag C.H. Beck, 2008).\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Arminius}}\n{{EB1911 poster|Arminius}}\n* [https://www.britannica.com/biography/Arminius Arminius] at the ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]''\n* [https://www.ancient.eu/Arminius/ Arminius] at the ''[[Ancient History Encyclopedia]]''\n* [http://www.westfaelische-geschichte.de/web840 \"''Arminius / Varus: Die Varusschlacht im Jahre 9 n. Chr.''\"] \u2013 LWL-Institut f\u00fcr westf\u00e4lische Regionalgeschichte (in German)\n* [https://www.dailymotion.com/video/x42a2ep \"Terry Jones' Barbarians: The Savage Goths\"] \u2013 includes a portion on Arminius\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070831030318/http://www.geschichte.uni-osnabrueck.de/projekt/start.html A description of Arminius and his fight against the Romans] (in German)\n* [http://www.thenational.ae/news/world/they-need-a-hero \"They Need a Hero\"] by Clay Risen in ''[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]'', October 9, 2009 \u2013 article on modern German views of Hermann and the 2,000th anniversary of the battle\n\n{{Germanic peoples}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arminius}}\n[[Category:Arminius| ]]\n[[Category:10s BC births]]\n[[Category:21 deaths]]\n[[Category:Cherusci rulers]]\n[[Category:Cherusci warriors]]\n[[Category:Myth of origins]]\n[[Category:Germanic paganism]]\n[[Category:Rebellions against the Roman Empire]]\n[[Category:1st-century rulers in Europe]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Chieftain of the Germanic Cherusci tribe}}\n{{About|the Germanic chieftain|other uses|Arminius (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name               = Arminius\n| office              = Prince and Chieftain of the Cherusci tribe\n| image              = Hermannsdenkmal statue.jpg\n| caption            = [[Hermannsdenkmal]] memorial\n| reign              =\n| coronation         =\n| full name          =\n| native_lang1       =\n| native_lang1_name1 = Armin, Hermann\n| birth_date         = 18/17 BC\n| birth_place        = [[Germania]]\n| death_date         = 21 AD (aged 37\u201338)\n| death_place        = [[Germania]]\n| burial_date        =\n| burial_place       = <!-- <br /> {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| predecessor        = [[Segimer]]\n| successor          = [[Italicus]]\n| spouse             = [[Thusnelda]]\n| issue              = [[Thumelicus]]\n| royal house        =\n| dynasty            =\n| father             = [[Segimer]]\n| mother             =\n| religion           = [[Germanic religion (aboriginal)|Germanic]]\n| signature          =\n}}\n\n'''Arminius''' ({{lang-de|Hermann}}; 18/17 BC \u2013 AD 21) was a chieftain of the [[Germanic peoples|Germanic]] [[Cherusci]] tribe who is best known for commanding an alliance of Germanic tribes at the [[Battle of the Teutoburg Forest]] in AD 9, in which three [[Roman legion]]s were destroyed. His victory at Teutoburg Forest would precipitate the [[Roman Empire]]'s permanent strategic withdrawal from [[Magna Germania]], and made a major contribution to the eventual [[Fall of the Western Roman Empire|fall]] of the [[Western Roman Empire]] several centuries later.<ref>{{cite book|author=Dr. Aaron Ralby|title=Atlas of Military History|url=https://archive.org/details/atlasofworldmili0000ralb|url-access=registration|year=2013|publisher=Parragon|isbn=978-1-4723-0963-1|page=[https://archive.org/details/atlasofworldmili0000ralb/page/241 241]|chapter=The Roman Legion: Refining Military Organization}}</ref> Modern historians have regarded Arminius' victory as Rome's greatest defeat.<ref name=\"Murdoch\">{{harvnb|Murdoch|2012|p=}}</ref> As it prevented the [[Romanization (cultural)|Romanization]] of the Germanic peoples, it has also been considered one of the most decisive battles in history,<ref name=\"Tucker\">{{harvnb|Tucker|2010|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=wHpVn68GCogC&pg=PA75 75]}}</ref><ref name=\"Cawthorne\">{{harvnb|Cawthorne|2012|p=}}</ref><ref name=\"Davis\">{{harvnb|Davis|1999|p=[https://books.google.com/books?hl=no&id=nv73QlQs9ocC&pg=PA68 68]}}</ref><ref name=\"Creasy\">{{harvnb|Creasy|2007|p=104}}</ref> and a turning point in [[History of the world|world history]].<ref name=\"Spectator\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.spectator.co.uk/books/20823/how-the-eagles-were-tamed/ |title=How the eagles were tamed |date=March 27, 2004 |magazine=[[The Spectator]] |accessdate=January 16, 2015 |quote=[[Theodor Mommsen|Mommsen]] referred to the Battle of the Teutoburg forest as a turning-point in world history.}}</ref> \n\nBorn a prince of the Cherusci tribe, Arminius was made a hostage of the Roman Empire as a child. Raised in [[Rome]], he was drafted into the [[Military of ancient Rome|Roman military]] at an early age, during which he was granted [[Roman citizenship]] and became a [[Equites|Roman knight]]. After serving with distinction in the [[Bellum Batonianum|Great Illyrian Revolt]], he was sent to [[Germania]] to aid the local governor [[Publius Quinctilius Varus]] in completing the Roman conquest of the Germanic tribes. While in this capacity, Arminius secretly plotted a Germanic revolt against Roman rule, which culminated in the ambush and destruction of three Roman legions in the Teutoburg Forest.\n\nIn the aftermath of the battle, Arminius fought retaliatory invasions by the Roman general [[Germanicus]] in the battles of [[Battle at Pontes Longi|Pontes Longi]], [[Battle of Idistaviso|Idistaviso]], and the [[Battle of the Angrivarian Wall|Angrivarian Wall]], and deposed a rival, the [[Marcomanni]] king [[Maroboduus]]. Germanic nobles, afraid of Arminius' growing power, assassinated him in AD 21. He was remembered in [[Saga|Germanic legends]] for generations afterwards.<ref name=\"Annals.02.88\"/> The Roman historian [[Tacitus]] designated Arminius as the liberator of the Germanic tribes and commended him for having fought the Roman Empire to a standstill at the peak of its power.<ref name=\"Annals.02.88\">[[Tacitus]]. [[wikisource:The Annals (Tacitus)/Book 2#63|The Annals.2.88]]. \"Assuredly he was the deliverer of Germany, one too who had defied Rome, not in her early rise, as other kings and generals, but in the height of her empire's glory, had fought, indeed, indecisive battles, yet in war remained unconquered. He completed thirty-seven years of life, twelve years of power, and he is still a theme of song among barbarous nations, though to Greek historians, who admire only their own achievements, he is unknown, and to Romans not as famous as he should be, while we extol the past and are indifferent to our own times.\"</ref>  \n\nDuring the [[unification of Germany]] in the 19th century, Arminius was hailed by [[German nationalism|German nationalists]] as a symbol of German unity and freedom.<ref name=\"Spiegel\">{{cite web |url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/battle-of-the-teutoburg-forest-germany-recalls-myth-that-created-the-nation-a-644913.html |title= Battle of the Teutoburg Forest: Germany Recalls Myth That Created the Nation |last1=Crossland |first1=David |date=August 28, 2009 |website=[[Spiegel Online|Spiegel Online International]] |publisher=[[Der Spiegel]] |accessdate=January 16, 2015}}</ref> Following [[World War II]], however, Arminius was [[Memory hole|omitted]] from German textbooks due to his association with militaristic nationalism, and many modern Germans are unaware of his story; the 2,000th anniversary of his victory at the Teutoburg Forest was only lightly commemorated in Germany.<ref name=\"Spiegel\"/>\n\n==Name==\n[[File:ArminiusbyGeorgeSStuart.jpg|thumb|left|200px|No known portrait image of Arminius exists from life. This likeness was created by artist and historian George S. Stuart from physical descriptions mentioned in historical records.]]\nThe [[etymology]] of the Latin name ''Arminius'' is unknown; confusion is further created by contemporary scholars who alternately referred to him as ''Armenus''.<ref name=\"MurdochEtymology\">{{cite book |last1=Murdoch |first1=Adrian |title=Rome's Greatest Defeat: Massacre in the Teutoburg Forest |date=2009 |publisher=The History Press |isbn=0750940166 |page=84}}</ref> [[Marcus Velleius Paterculus]], in his ''Historiae'', mentions him as \"Arminius, the son of Sigimer, a prince of [the German] nation\" and states he \"attained the dignity of [[Equites|equestrian rank]]\".<ref>{{cite book|url=http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Velleius_Paterculus/2D*.html|title=The Roman History|author=C. Velleius Paterculus|publisher=Loeb Classical Library|date=1924|page=118}}</ref> Due to [[Roman naming conventions#Foreign names|Roman naming conventions]] of the time, it is likely ''Arminius'' is an adopted name granted to him upon citizenship, or otherwise not his Cheruscan name; although the theory that the name alludes to prior service on the [[Lesser Armenia#Roman\u2013Persian_wars|eastern frontier of the Roman empire]]is now largely discredited.<ref name=\"MurdochEtymology\" />\n\nThe German translation of ''Arminius'' as ''Hermann'' dates from the 16th century, possibly first by [[Martin Luther]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Arminius into Hermann: History into Legend|author=Herbert W. Benario|journal=Greece and Rome|volume=51|issue=1|date=April 2004|pages=83\u201394|doi= 10.1093/gr/51.1.83}}</ref> In German, Arminius is traditionally known as ''Hermann der Cherusker'' (\"Hermann the Cheruscan\") or ''Hermann der Cheruskerf\u00fcrst'' (\"Hermann the Cheruscan Prince\"). Hermann etymologically means \"Man of War\", coming from the [[Old High German]] ''heri'' \"war\" and ''man'' \"man\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=F\u00f6rstemann|first1=Ernst Wilhelm|title=Altdeutsches Namenbuch|date=1900|publisher=Nabu Press|isbn=9781270714996|language=German}}</ref><ref>http://www.vorname.com/name,Hermann.html</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:Stammbaum ADBSegest.jpg|right|400px|thumb|Relatives of Arminius]]\nBorn in 18 or 17 BC in [[Germania]], Arminius was the son of the Cheruscan chief [[Segimerus]] (German: ''Segimer''; Proto-Germanic: ''Sigimariz''; Old English: ''Sigemaer''). He lived in Rome as a hostage during his youth, where he learned to speak [[Latin]] and trained as a Roman military commander alongside his younger brother [[Flavus (son of Segimerus)|Flavus]]. He served in the Roman army between AD 1 and 6, and received a military education as well as [[Roman citizenship]] and the status of [[equite]] before returning to Germania.<ref name=\"Durschmied\">{{harvnb|Durschmied|2013|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=ESY980GKv3cC&pg=PA1759 p. 1759]}}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Arminius|encyclopedia=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Ultimate Reference Suite]]|year=2014|publisher=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc.|Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]|location=Chicago}}</ref> These experiences gave him knowledge of Roman politics and military tactics, which allowed him to successfully anticipate enemy battle maneuvers during his later campaigns against the Roman army.\n\n===Battle of the Teutoburg Forest===\n{{Main article|Battle of the Teutoburg Forest}}\n[[File:Magna Germania before the battle of the Teutoburg Forest.png|right|thumb|Magna Germania in AD 9. The yellow legend represents the areas controlled by the [[Roman Republic]] in 31 BC, the shades of green represent gradually conquered territories under the reign of [[Augustus]], and pink areas on the map represent tributary tribes.]]\nAround the year AD 4, Arminius assumed command of a Cheruscan detachment of Roman auxiliary forces, probably while fighting in the [[Pannonian]] wars on the [[Balkan peninsula]]. He returned to northern Germania in AD 7 or 8, where the Roman Empire had established secure control of the territories just east of the [[Rhine]], along the [[Lippe]] and [[Main (river)|Main]] rivers, and was now seeking to extend its hegemony eastward to the [[Weser]] and [[Elbe]] rivers, under [[Publius Quinctilius Varus]], a high-ranking administrative official appointed by [[Augustus]] as governor. Arminius began plotting to unite various Germanic tribes in order to thwart Roman efforts to incorporate their lands into the empire. This proved a difficult task, as the tribes were strongly independent and many were traditionally enemies of each other.\n\nBetween AD 6 and 9, the Romans were forced to move eight of the eleven legions present in Germania east of the Rhine to crush a [[Great Illyrian Revolt|rebellion]] in the [[Balkans]],<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.livius.org/le-lh/legio/v_alaudae.html | date = September 2010 | title = Legio V Alaudae | publisher = www.livius.org}}</ref> leaving Varus with only three legions to face the Germans. An additional two legions, under the command of [[Lucius Nonius Asprenas (suffect consul AD 6)|Lucius Nonius Asprenas]], were stationed in [[Moguntiacum]].<ref>Syme, pg. 60</ref> Arminius saw this as the perfect opportunity to defeat Varus.<ref>Velleius Paterculus, ''Compendium of Roman History'' 2, 109, 5; [[Cassius Dio]], ''Roman History'' 55, 28, 6\u20137</ref>\n\n[[File:Otto Albert Koch Varusschlacht 1909.jpg|left|thumb|''Varusschlacht'', Otto Albert Koch (1909)]]\nIn the autumn of AD 9, the 25-year-old Arminius brought to Varus a false report of rebellion in northern Germany. He persuaded Varus to divert the three legions under his command (composed of the [[Legio XVII|17th]], [[Legio XVIII|18th]], and [[Legio XIX|19th]] [[Roman legion|legions]], plus three [[cavalry]] detachments and six [[cohort (military unit)|cohorts]] of auxiliaries), which were at the time marching to winter quarters, to suppress the rebellion. Varus and his legions marched right into the trap that Arminius had set for them near [[Kalkriese]]. Arminius' tribe, the [[Cherusci]], and their allies the [[Marsi (Germanic)|Marsi]], [[Chatti]], [[Bructeri]], [[Chauci]], and [[Sicambri]] (five out of at least fifty Germanic tribes at the time)<ref name=\"Spiegel\"/> ambushed and annihilated Varus' entire army, totaling over 20,000 men, as it marched along a narrow road through a dense forest. Recent archaeological finds show the long-debated location of the three-day battle was almost certainly near Kalkriese Hill, about 20&nbsp;km north of present-day [[Osnabr\u00fcck]]. When defeat was certain, Varus committed suicide by falling on his sword. The battle was one of the most devastating defeats Rome suffered in its history. Arminius' success in destroying three entire legions and driving the Romans out of Germany marked a high point of Germanic power for centuries. Roman attempts to reconquer Germania failed, although they did eventually manage to break Arminius' carefully coordinated alliance.\n\n===Roman retaliation, inter-tribal conflicts, and death===\n[[File:Blick-\u00fcber-den-Teutoburger-Wald1.jpg|thumb|right|300px|View over the [[Teutoburg Forest]]]]\nAfter the battle, the Germans quickly annihilated every trace of Roman presence east of the Rhine. Roman settlements such as the [[Waldgirmes Forum]] were abandoned. The vastly outnumbered Roman garrison of Aliso (present-day [[Haltern am See]]), under the command of the prefect Lucius Cedicius, inflicted heavy losses on the Germans before retreating into [[Gaul]], resisting long enough for Lucius Nonius Asprenas to organize the Roman defense on the Rhine and [[Tiberius]] to arrive with a new army. This prevented Arminius from crossing the Rhine and invading Gaul.<ref>Velleius Paterculus, Compendium of Roman History II, 120, 4; Cassius Dio, Roman History LVI, 22, 2a-2b</ref>\n\nBetween AD 14 and 16, [[Germanicus]] led punitive operations into Germany, fighting Arminius to a draw in the [[Battle at Pontes Longi]] and twice defeating him (according to Tacitus): first in the [[Battle of Idistaviso]] and later at the [[Battle of the Angrivarian Wall]]. In AD 15, Roman troops managed to recapture one of the three [[aquila (Roman)|legionary eagles]] lost in the Battle of the Teutoburg Forest. In AD 16, a second eagle was retrieved.<ref>Tac. ''Ann''. 1.60.4, 2.25.2</ref> Tiberius denied the request of Germanicus to launch an additional campaign for AD 17, however, having decided the frontier with Germania would stand at the Rhine river. Instead, he offered Germanicus the honor of a triumph for his two victories. The third Roman eagle was recovered in AD 41 by Publius Gabinius, under the emperor [[Claudius]].<ref>Dio 60.8.7.</ref> Arminius also faced opposition from his father-in-law and other pro-Roman Germanic leaders.<ref>Tac. ''Ann''. 1.54\u201359.</ref> His brother [[Flavus (son of Segimerus)|Flavus]], who had been raised alongside him in Rome, remained loyal to the Roman Empire and fought under Germanicus against Arminius at the Battle of Idistaviso. With the end of the Roman threat, a war broke out between Arminius and [[Maroboduus|Marbod]], king of the [[Marcomanni]]. It ended with Marbod fleeing to [[Ravenna]] and Roman protection, but Arminius failed to break into the \"natural fortification\" of [[Bohemia]], and the war ended in stalemate.\n\nIn AD 19, Germanicus died in [[Antioch]] under circumstances which led many to believe he had been poisoned by his opponents. Arminius died two years later, in AD 21, murdered by opponents within his own tribe who felt that he was becoming too powerful.<ref name=\"tacit\">Tacitus, The Annals [[s:The Annals (Tacitus)/Book 2#88|2.88]]</ref><ref>[[Tacitus]], ''Annals'' 2.22 ff.; [[Suetonius]], ''Caligula'' 1.4; Dio 57.18.1; on Arminius' assassination, Tac. ''Ann''. 2.88;</ref> Tiberius allegedly had refused an earlier offer from a Chatti nobleman to poison Arminius: \"It was not by secret treachery but openly and by arms that the people of Rome avenged themselves on their enemies.\"<ref>Tac. ''Ann''. 2.87\u201388.</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nArminius married a princess named [[Thusnelda]], whose name is preserved only by [[Strabo]]. She was captured by the Romans while pregnant, so her son [[Thumelicus]] grew up in Roman captivity. [[Tacitus]] describes him as having an unusual story, which the historian promises to tell, but this part of Tacitus' writings has since been lost.\n\nArminius' victory against the Roman legions in the Teutoburg Forest had a far-reaching effect on the subsequent history of both the ancient [[Germanic peoples]] and on the Roman Empire. The Romans made no further concerted efforts to conquer and permanently hold Germania beyond the Rhine and the [[Agri Decumates]]. Numerous modern historians have regarded Arminius' victory as \"Rome's greatest defeat\"<ref name=\"Murdoch\"/> and one of the most decisive battles in history.<ref name=\"Tucker\"/><ref name=\"Cawthorne\"/><ref name=\"Davis\"/><ref name=\"Creasy\"/><ref name=\"Spectator\"/><ref name=\"Durschmied\"/>\n\n===Rome===\n[[File:Arminius pushkin.jpg|right|thumb|This Roman sculpture of a young man is sometimes identified as Arminius<ref name=britannica>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Arminius|title=Arminius|work=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Thusnelda Loggia dei Lanzi 2005 09 13.jpg|thumb|upright=0.7|Thusnelda statue in [[Loggia dei Lanzi]], Florence]]\nIn the accounts of his Roman enemies, Arminius is highly regarded for his military leadership and as a defender of the liberty of his people. Based on these records, the story of Arminius was revived in the 16th century with the recovery of the histories of [[Tacitus]], who wrote in his ''Annales II, 88'':\n\n{{quote|text=Arminius, without doubt Germania's liberator, who challenged the Roman people not in its beginnings like other kings and leaders, but in the peak of its empire; in battles with changing success, undefeated in the war.<ref>{{cite book|title=Arminius the Liberator: Myth and Ideology|first=Martin M.|last=Winkler|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|date=2016|isbn=9780190252915|page=30}}</ref>}}\n\nArminius was not the only reason for Rome's change of policy towards Germania. Politics also played a factor; emperors found they could rarely trust a large army to a potential rival, though Augustus had enough loyal family members to wage his wars. Also, Augustus, in his 40-year reign, had annexed many territories still at the beginning of the process of Romanization. Tiberius, who succeeded Augustus in AD 14, decided that Germania was a far less developed land, possessing few villages and only a small food surplus, and therefore was not currently important to Rome. Conquering Germania would require a commitment too burdensome for the imperial finances and an excessive expenditure of military force.\n\nModern scholars have pointed out that the [[Rhine]] was a more practical boundary for the Roman Empire than any other river in Germania. Armies on the Rhine could be supplied from the [[Mediterranean Sea]] via the [[Rh\u00f4ne]], [[Sa\u00f4ne]], and [[Moselle (river)|Mosel]], with only a brief area of portage. Armies on the [[Elbe]], however, would had to have been supplied by extensive overland routes or by ships travelling the hazardous Atlantic. Economically, the Rhine already had towns and sizable villages at the time of the Gallic conquest. The Rhine was significantly more accessible from Rome and better equipped to supply sizable garrisons than the regions beyond.<ref>Peter Heather (2006). ''The Fall of the Roman Empire: A New History of Rome and the Barbarians''.</ref>\n\nRome chose no longer to rule directly in Germania east of the [[Rhine]] and north of the [[Danube]], instead preferring to exert indirect influence by appointing [[client king]]s, which was cheaper than military campaigns. [[Italicus]], nephew of Arminius, was appointed king of the Cherusci; [[Vangio and Sido]] became [[vassal]] princes of the powerful [[Suebi]], etc.<ref>[[Annals (Tacitus)|Tacitus]], Book 12 [verse 27 to 31]</ref> When indirect methods proved insufficient to control the Germanic tribes beyond the Rhine, Roman emperors occasionally led devastating punitive campaigns deep into Germania. One of them, led by the Roman emperor [[Maximinus Thrax]], resulted in a Roman victory in AD 235 at the [[Battle at the Harzhorn]] Hill,<ref>Historia Augusta, ''The Two Maximini'' 12:1\u20134; Herodian, ''Roman History'', Book 7:2:3</ref> located in the modern German state of [[Lower Saxony]], east of the [[Weser]] river, between the towns of [[Kalefeld]] and [[Bad Gandersheim]].\n\n===Old Germanic sagas===\nIn the early 19th century, attempts were made to show that the story of Arminius and his victory may have lived on in the [[Old Norse]] [[sagas]],<ref>{{cite journal|title=Ueber den Ursprung der Siegfriedsage|author=A. Giesebrecht|journal=Germania|issue=2|year=1837|url=https://archive.org/details/UeberDenUrsprungDerSiegfriedsage/}}</ref> in the form of the dragon slayer [[Sigurd]] of the [[V\u00f6lsunga saga]] and the [[Nibelungenlied]]. An Icelandic account<ref>{{cite journal|title= Nikulas Bergsson, Arnamagn\u00e6an Collection manuscript 194, 8yo |author=unknown | year=1387}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title= Altnordische Kosmographie: Studien und Quellen zu Weltbild und Weltbeschreibung in Norwegen und in Island vom 12. bis zum 14. Jahrhundert |author= Simek, R. |journal= Berlin/New York | year=1990}}</ref>\nstates that Sigurd \"slew the dragon\" in the Gnitaheidr\u2014today the suburb Knetterheide of the city of [[Bad Salzuflen]], located at a strategic site on the [[Werre]] river which could very well have been the point of departure of Varus' legions on their way to their doom in the Teutoburg Forest. One of the foremost Scandinavian scholars of the 19th century, [[Gu\u00f0brandur Vigf\u00fasson]],<ref>{{cite book|title=Grimm centenary; Sigfred-Arminivs, and other papers\n|author= G. Vigfusson, F. York Powell|publisher=Oxford Clarendon Press|year=1886|url=https://archive.org/details/grimmcentenarysi00gudb}}</ref> identified Sigurd as Arminius. This educated guess was also picked up by [[Otto H\u00f6fler]], who was a prominent [[National Socialist]] academic during World War II.<ref>O. H\u00f6fler, \"Siegfried Arminius und die Symbolik,\"  ''Heidelberg'' (1961), 60\u201364, and also in ''Siegfried, Arminius und der Nibelungenhort'' (Vienna 1978); F.G. Gentry, W. McConnell, W. Wunderlich (eds.), ''The Nibelungen Tradition. An Encyclopedia'' (New York\u2013London 2002), article \"Sigurd\".</ref>\n\n===German nationalism===\nDuring the [[unification of Germany]] in the 19th century, Arminius was hailed as a symbol of German unity and freedom.<ref name=\"Spiegel\"/> In Germany, the name ''Arminius'' was interpreted as reflecting the name ''Hermann'' by [[Martin Luther]], who saw Arminius as a symbol of the German people and their fight against Rome.<ref>{{cite journal|title=German Pagan Antiquity in Lutheran Historical Thought|author=W. Bradford Smith|journal=The Journal of the Historical Society|volume=4|issue=3|year=2004|pages=351\u201374 | doi = 10.1111/j.1529-921X.2004.00104.x}}</ref> ''Hermann der Cheruskerf\u00fcrst'' became an emblem of the revival of [[German nationalism]] fueled by the [[Napoleonic Wars]] in the 19th century.<ref name=\"Klein/K\u00e4ppel\">Dorothea Klein (ed.), Lutz K\u00e4ppel (ed.): ''Das diskursive Erbe Europas: Antike und Antikerezeption''. Peter Lang, 2008, {{ISBN|9783631560136}},  [https://books.google.com/books?id=yvfqcAjU9wsC&pg=PA329 p. 329]</ref>\n\n[[File:Gehrts Armin verabschiedet sich von Thusnelda 1884.jpg|thumb|Arminius says goodbye to [[Thusnelda]], [[Johannes Gehrts]] (1884)]]\nIn 1808, [[Heinrich von Kleist]] wrote the play ''[[Die Hermannsschlacht (Kleist)|Die Hermannsschlacht]]'',<ref>Heinrich von Kleist: Die Herrmannsschlacht. Ein Drama [1808] (Frankfurt am Main and Basel: Stroemfeld-Roter Stern, 2001).</ref> but with Napoleon's [[Battle of Wagram|victory at Wagram]] it remained in manuscript, being published in 1821 and not staged until 1860. The play has been revived repeatedly at moments propitious for raw expressions of [[National Romanticism]] and was especially popular during the [[Third Reich]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia| encyclopedia=The Literary Encyclopedia | title=Die Hermannsschlacht | first=William C | last=Reeve | year=2004 | url= http://www.litencyc.com/php/sworks.php?rec=true&UID=13117 | publisher=The Literary Dictionary Company | accessdate=2006-09-06}}</ref>\n\nIn 1838, construction was started on a massive statue of Arminius, known as the ''[[Hermannsdenkmal]]'', on a hill near [[Detmold]] in the Teutoburg Forest; it was finally completed and dedicated during the early years of the Second [[German Empire]] in the wake of the German victory over France in the [[Franco-Prussian War]] of 1870\u20131871. The monument has been a major tourist attraction ever since, as has the [[Hermann Heights Monument]], a similar statue erected in [[New Ulm, Minnesota]] in the United States in 1897. The Hermann Heights monument was erected by the [[Sons of Hermann]], a fraternal organization formed by [[German American]]s in New York City in 1840 that flourished during the 19th century in American cities with large populations of German origin. [[Hermann, Missouri]], a town on the Missouri River founded in the 1830s and incorporated in 1845, was also named for Arminius.\n\nFollowing the rise of [[Nazi Germany]], fueled by aggressive German nationalism, and its subsequent defeat in [[World War II]], Arminius became a lesser-known figure among [[West Germany|West Germans]] and many schools shunned away from teaching his story in any detail due to its previous association with nationalism.<ref name=\"Spiegel\"/> There was, however, a somewhat different perception in [[East Germany]]. In East Germany, Arminius, based on a [[Marxism|Marxist]] reading of history, came to be seen as a revolutionary figure of sorts, leading German tribes in a fight against the Roman slaveholder society (''Sklavenhaltergesellschaft''). In the context of the [[Cold War]], Arminius was interpreted as symbolic of [[socialism]], with Rome being a symbol of the [[capitalism|capitalist]] United States as an oppressive empire.<ref name=zeit> Tillmann Bendikowski: [http://www.zeit.de/2008/45/DOS-varus-schlacht ''Deutsche Geschichte \u2013 Mythos einer Schlacht'']. Zeit Online, 2008-11-04 (German)</ref>\n\nThe 2,000-year anniversary of the Battle of the Teutoburg Forest, in 2009, was celebrated with restraint in Germany, avoiding \"flag-waving festivals\" and other gestures that might be interpreted as nationalism.<ref name=\"Spiegel\"/> According to ''[[Der Spiegel]]'': \"The old nationalism has been replaced by an easy-going [[patriotism]] that mainly manifests itself at sporting events like the soccer<!-- Do not change this to \"football\". This is a direct quote. --> [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]].\"<ref name=\"Spiegel\"/> The German Bundesliga football club [[DSC Arminia Bielefeld]] is named after Arminius. The 2,000-year anniversary of the battle was also celebrated in New Ulm, Minnesota without restraint. There were mock battles between Romans and club-wielding barbarians and also a lecture series in an auditorium.<ref>[https://www.twincities.com/2009/09/20/new-ulm-celebrates-2000th-anniversary-of-battle/ New Ulm celebrates 2,000th anniversary of battle]</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n{{In popular culture|date=July 2017}}\n;Music\n* ''[[Arminio (Biber)|Arminio]]'' is a 1692 opera about Arminius by the Bohemian-Austrian composer [[Heinrich Ignaz Franz Biber]].\n* ''[[Arminio]]'' is a 1736 opera about Arminius by [[George Frideric Handel]].\n* ''[[Arminius (Bruch)|Arminius]]'' is an 1877 oratorio about Arminius by the German composer [[Max Bruch]].\n* ''Schlammschlacht'' is a 2015 spoken word song about Arminius and the [[Battle of the Teutoburg Forest]] by the Danish band [[Heilung]].\n;Historical novels\n* At the end of [[G. A. Henty]]'s 1887 ''The Young Carthaginan'' about the [[Second Punic War]], the main fictional character, Malchus, a cousin of [[Hannibal]], decides to settle with the tribes north of the Alps and becomes an ancestor of Arminius.\n* In the Czech novel ''[[Zlomen\u00fd Me\u010d]]'' (\"Broken sword\") by [[Eduard \u0160torch]], published in 1932, Arminius challenges the [[Marcomanni]] king [[Marobodus]] for the leadership of the Germanic tribes. The novel mistakenly shows the Celtic tribesmen as being Slavs to support the rising Slavonic identification of the nationalistic Czechs.\n* [[Robert Graves]]' fictional autobiography ''[[I, Claudius]]'' (1934) includes a description of Arminius' campaigns, where he is called \"Hermann\"; he is killed by members of his own family when he tries to \"issue orders like a king\".\n* Arminius is a character in ''[[Give Me Back My Legions!]]'', a 2009 historical novel by [[Harry Turtledove]] that retells the story of the Battle of the Teutoburg Forest.\n;Film\n* In the 2016 American docudrama ''[[Barbarians Rising]]'', Arminius is played by [[Tom Hopper]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Ancient Germanic culture}}\n* [[Ariovistus]]\n* [[Bato (Breucian chieftain)]]\n* [[Bato (Daesitiate chieftain)]]\n* [[Boudica]]\n* [[Divico]]\n* [[Flavus (son of Segimerus)|Flavus]]\n* [[Gaius Julius Civilis]]\n* [[Teutobod]]\n* [[Vercingetorix]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book |last=Cawthorne |first=Nigel |authorlink=Nigel Cawthorne |date=July 24, 2012 |title=Battles That Changed History: An Encyclopedia of World Conflict |url=https://books.google.com/?id=wHpVn68GCogC&pg=PA75 |location= |publisher=Arcturus Publishing |pages=75\u201377 |isbn=978-1848589544 |accessdate= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Davis |first=Paul K. |authorlink=Paul K. Davis (historian) |date=1999 |title=100 Decisive Battles: From Ancient Times to the Present |url=https://books.google.no/books?id=nv73QlQs9ocC |location= |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |pages=68\u201371 |isbn=0195143663 |accessdate= |ref=harv}}\n* Andreas D\u00f6rner, ''Politischer Mythos und symbolische Politik. Der Hermannmythos: Zur Entstehung des Nationalbewu\u00dftseins der Deutschen'' (Reinbek: Rowohlt, 1996).\n* {{cite book |last=Durschmied |first=Erik |authorlink=Erik Durschmied |date=April 13, 2013 |title=The Weather Factor: How Nature Has Changed History |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ESY980GKv3cC&pg=PA1751 |location= |publisher=[[Hachette (publisher)|Hachette UK]] |pages=1751\u201370|isbn=978-1444769654 |accessdate= |ref=harv}}\n* Gesa von Essen, ''Hermannsschlachten. Germanen- und R\u00f6merbilder in der Literatur des 18. und 19. Jahrhunderts'' (G\u00f6ttingen: Wallstein, 1998).\n* Richard Kuehnemund, ''Arminius or the Rise of a National Symbol in Literature. From Hutten to Grabbe'' (New York: AMS Press, 1966).\n* Herfried M\u00fcnkler / Hans Gr\u00fcnberger: Arminius/ Hermann als nationales Symbol im Diskurs der deutschen Humanisten 1500\u20131570, In: Herfried M\u00fcnkler / Hans Gr\u00fcnberger / Kathrin Mayer, ''Nationenbildung. Die Nationalisierung Europas im Diskurs humanistischer Intellektueller. Italien und Deutschland'' (Berlin: Akademie, 1998), pp.&nbsp;263\u2013308.\n* {{cite book |last=Murdoch |first=Adrian |date=1 December 2012 |title=Rome's Greatest Defeat: Massacre in the Teutoburg Forest |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Pao7AwAAQBAJ |location= |publisher=[[The History Press]] |page= |isbn=978-0752494555 |accessdate=|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Tucker |first=Spencer |authorlink=Spencer C. Tucker |date=2010 |title=Battles That Changed History: An Encyclopedia of World Conflict |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wHpVn68GCogC |location= |publisher=[[ABC-CLIO]] |page= |isbn=978-1598844290 |accessdate= |ref=harv}}\n* Martina Wagner-Egelhaaf (Ed.), ''Hermanns Schlachten. Zur Literaturgeschichte eines nationalen Mythos'' (Bielefeld: Aisthesis, 2008).\n* Reinhard Wolters, ''Die Schlacht im Teutoburger Wald: Arminius, Varus und das roemische Germanien'' (M\u00fcnchen: Verlag C.H. Beck, 2008).\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Arminius}}\n{{EB1911 poster|Arminius}}\n* [https://www.britannica.com/biography/Arminius Arminius] at the ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]''\n* [https://www.ancient.eu/Arminius/ Arminius] at the ''[[Ancient History Encyclopedia]]''\n* [http://www.westfaelische-geschichte.de/web840 \"''Arminius / Varus: Die Varusschlacht im Jahre 9 n. Chr.''\"] \u2013 LWL-Institut f\u00fcr westf\u00e4lische Regionalgeschichte (in German)\n* [https://www.dailymotion.com/video/x42a2ep \"Terry Jones' Barbarians: The Savage Goths\"] \u2013 includes a portion on Arminius\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070831030318/http://www.geschichte.uni-osnabrueck.de/projekt/start.html A description of Arminius and his fight against the Romans] (in German)\n* [http://www.thenational.ae/news/world/they-need-a-hero \"They Need a Hero\"] by Clay Risen in ''[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]'', October 9, 2009 \u2013 article on modern German views of Hermann and the 2,000th anniversary of the battle\n\n{{Germanic peoples}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arminius}}\n[[Category:Arminius| ]]\n[[Category:10s BC births]]\n[[Category:21 deaths]]\n[[Category:Cherusci rulers]]\n[[Category:Cherusci warriors]]\n[[Category:Myth of origins]]\n[[Category:Germanic paganism]]\n[[Category:Rebellions against the Roman Empire]]\n[[Category:1st-century rulers in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "Babylon717", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eName", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arminius"}
{"title_page": "Norsk Spisevognselskap", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name   = Norsk Spisevognselskap\n| logo   = [[File:Norsk Spisevognselskap logo.png|200px]]\n| caption         =\n| type   = [[Statsforetak|State enterprise]]\n| fate           = [[Mergers and acquisitions|Merger]]\n| Predecessor    =\n| successor      = [[Narvesen]]\n| foundation     = 21 December 1918\n| defunct        = 1 January 1975\n| location       = [[Oslo]], [[Norway]]\n| industry       = [[Rail transport]]\n| products       = [[Mobile catering]]\n| key_people     =\n| num_employees  = 591 (1949){{Sfn|Ottersland|2011|p=25}}\n| parent         = [[Norwegian State Railways]]\n| subsid         =\n}}\n\n'''Norsk Spisevognselskap A/S''', often abbreviated '''NSS''' or shortened to '''Spisevognselskapet''' ([[Norwegian language|Norwegian]] for \"The Dining Car Company\"), was a [[Norway|Norwegian]] [[government-owned corporation|state enterprise]] which operated [[restaurant carriage]]s on [[rail transport in Norway|Norwegian trains]] and restaurants at [[railway station]]s and [[Hotel#Railway hotels|railway hotels]]. The company was established in December 1918, and started a catering service in 1919. Originally owned by the [[Hoved Line|Norwegian Trunk Railway]], it was acquired by the state in 1926. Meals served in the restaurant carriages were relatively expensive, although they were available to all passengers. In the 1950s, the company began using serving trolleys on trains.\n\nIn January 1975, NSS [[Mergers and acquisitions|merged]] with the convenience-store chain [[Narvesen|Narvesen Kioskkompani]] into a new company called Narvesen\u2013Spisevognselskapet. This enterprise was partly owned by the [[Norwegian State Railways]] (NSB) and [[Fritt Ord (organization)|Fritt Ord]], before it merged with the [[Reitan Group]] and was delisted from the [[Oslo Stock Exchange]].\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Spisevognbergensbanen.jpg|thumb|left|Restaurant carriage on a [[Bergen Line]] train in 1909|alt=restaurant carriage, with tables set for dinner]]\nFrom the 1854 establishment of railways in Norway to 1909, no dining service was offered aboard trains; passengers were allowed to bring food with them. Train stations also lacked dining facilities. The first dining service was started by restaurateur Carl Christiansen.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=13}} He established the restaurant at [[Drammen Station]], and in 1907 was asked by NSB to establish a dining service aboard the express trains on the [[Bergen Line]], which would open in 1909. After investigating similar operations in England and Germany, he ordered two carriages from [[Skabo Jernbanevognfabrikk]].{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=14}} These were to be paid for by the state, but the [[Parliament of Norway]] delayed the grants after a long debate regarding the suitability of restaurant carriages on trains. The plans were opposed by the [[Teetotalism|teetotaler]] faction of Parliament, but there was a majority in favor of dining service. To get the carriages in time, Christiansen personally guaranteed the production cost in case a state grant was not allocated. After the parliamentary decision, the cost of the carriages was refunded by NSB.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=15}} In 1910, when [[President of the United States]] [[Theodore Roosevelt]] visited [[Oslo]] to receive the [[Nobel Peace Prize]], several restaurant carriages were ordered solely for the occasion. Two years later, restaurant carriages were put in regular service on the [[\u00d8stfold Line]].{{Sfn|Ottersland|2011|p=24}}\n\n==Early days==\n[[File:Norsk Spisevognselskap at Oslo \u00d8.jpg|thumb|Norsk Spisevognselskap restaurant carriage at [[Oslo East Station]] in 1935|alt=Outside of restaurant carriage, 1935]]\nIn 1916, the executive board of the state railways wanted to centralise the operation of restaurant carriages and the most important station restaurants in Norway under one management. The board stated that they wanted to minimise the conflict of interest between the railway company and the dining-car operator. They also saw centralising operations as a way to allocate a larger share of the revenue to the railway company, and to ensure a high quality of service on new lines.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=22}} At that time the [[S\u00f8rland Line]] and [[Dovre Line]] were in the planning stages, and the NSB intended to introduce dining services on these when they opened.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=28}} [[Oslo East Station]] and its restaurant were operated by the private [[Hoved Line|Norwegian Trunk Railway]]. In an agreement signed on 18 September 1918 both railway companies agreed that a new restaurant operator would be controlled by the Norwegian Trunk Railway, but this company had to abide by the NSB's decision of how many restaurant carriages to operate on any line.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=23}}\n\nThis model was inspired by Sweden, where a separate dining company had been established; this company paid the railway company part of its revenue and a fixed fee per restaurant carriage. The Swedish model involved including the operation of station restaurants at locations where the restaurant carriages would have depots.<!--What does the word \"depots\" mean in this sentence?-->{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=29}} On 21 December 1918, A.S Norsk Spisevognselskap was established with a share capital of 200,000 [[Norwegian krone]] (NOK). It had 20 shares; 17 were owned by the Trunk Railway, and one by each of three directors: [[Waldemar Stoud Platou]], Gotfred Furuholmen and [[Christian Emil Stoud Platou]]\u2014the former representing the Trunk Railway and the latter being director-general of the NSB.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=24}} In January 1919, Waldemar Platou was appointed chair and Christiansen managing director. The company took over Christiansen's four restaurant carriages and the restaurant at Oslo \u00d8 on 1 April 1919.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=27}}\n\nOn 2 February 1926, Parliament voted to [[nationalise]] the Trunk Railway. During the debate, the organisation of Spisevognselskapet was criticised; with the nationalisation, the state became the sole owner of Spisevognselskapet. On 31 March 1927, the [[Ministry of Labour (Norway 1885\u20131946)|Ministry of Labour]] recommended that the company remain a state-owned limited company; the minority in parliament wanted a state enterprise.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=31}} During the 1930s, [[Sigurd Astrup]] was managing director of Norsk Spisevognselskap.{{Sfn|Hoffstad (ed.)|1935|p=42}} In 1948, [[Erling Mossige]] was appointed managing director of the company. He was succeeded by [[Knut Tvedt]] in 1960.{{Sfn|Steenstrup (ed.)|1973|pp=393\u201394}} The company had 75 employees in 1919, and 591 in 1949.{{Sfn|Ottersland|2011|p=25}}\n\n==Restaurant carriages==\n[[File:Norsk Spisevognselskap dining in 1947.jpg|thumb|left|Dining in 1947|alt=Waiter serving party of four in 1947]]\nThe restaurant carriages of the NSS were open to everyone, but dining was so expensive that only passengers travelling in first class used the service. Usually, three or four dishes were offered in the restaurant carriages. A four-course dinner cost five [[Norwegian kroner]] in the 1920s, which was expensive at the time.{{Sfn|Ottersland|2011|p=26}} Warm dishes, such as soups and sauces, were usually prepared at a small stove in the restaurant carriage's kitchen. On busy days, prepared steaks were delivered from rail depots. The kitchens were staffed by two maids and one attendant. Blocks of ice were often used instead of [[refrigerator]]s.{{Sfn|Ottersland|2011|p=26}}\n\nWith the opening of the Dovre Line, Spisevognselskapet established dining-car service on 25 June 1921.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=39}} In 1921 a train ride from Kristiania to [[Trondheim]] lasted approximately 15 hours, and the average waiting time at each station was between 10 and 15 minutes.{{Sfn|Ottersland|2011|p=26}} On 1 July 1925 dining service was introduced on the [[Valdres Line]], from 1 July 1926 on the [[Brevik Line]], from May 1934 on the [[Nordland Line]] and from 15 May 1936 on the [[R\u00f8ros Line]]. In 1948 210,000 meals were served on board, in addition to sandwiches and drinks. The company also offered a light breakfast on night trains on the [[Kongsvinger Line|Kongsvinger]], \u00d8stfold and Dovre lines.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=39}} During the [[Second World War]], dining-car service was discontinued.\n\nAfter the war trains faced competition from [[aviation]] and automobiles, and serving trolleys were installed on Norwegian trains.{{Sfn|Ottersland|2011|p=26}} In 1965 cart service on trains was centralised and standardised; food service was faster, and prices were lowered. During the 1970s cafeteria cars were used, where passengers could serve themselves.{{Sfn|Ottersland|2011|p=26}}\n\n==Restaurants==\n[[File:Bjorli restaurant.jpg|thumb|Restaurant at [[Bjorli Station]]|alt=Large, high-ceilinged restaurant in Bjorli Station]]\nNSS derived most of its revenue from the operation of restaurants at railway stations; in 1939, this amounted to 80%.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=49}} Initially, the company operated the restaurant at Oslo \u00d8; from 1921, it also took over operation of the restaurants at [[Oslo Vestbanestasjon|Oslo West Station]], [[Hamar Station|Hamar]], [[Koppang Station|Koppang]], [[Oppdal Station|Opdal]] and [[Elverum Station|Elverum]]. The following year, four more restaurants were added: [[St\u00f8ren Station|St\u00f8ren]], [[Myrdal Station|Myrdal]], [[Dokka Station|Dokka]] and [[Hell Station|Hell]]. NSS also established its first kiosk, at [[Bergen Station]].{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=50}} In 1923, the company was allowed to take over all restaurants in the railway districts of Oslo and Hamar; by 1925, it had taken over operation of the restaurants at [[Lillehammer Station|Lillehammer]], [[H\u00f8nefoss Station|H\u00f8nefoss]], [[Jessheim Station|Jessheim]], [[Kornsj\u00f8 Station|Kornsj\u00f8]], [[Halden Station|Halden]], [[Ski Station|Ski]], [[Eidsvoll Station|Eidsvoll]], [[Otta Station|Otta]], [[Domb\u00e5s Station|Domb\u00e5s]], [[\u00c5ndalsnes Station|\u00c5ndalsnes]], [[Kongsvinger Station|Kongsvinger]], [[Trondheim Central Station|Trondheim]], [[Rena Station|Rena]], [[Roa Station|Roa]], [[Ringebu Station|Ringebu]], [[Bjorli Station|Bjorli]] and [[Finse Station|Finse]].{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=51}}\n\nAfter this NSS decided not to obtain many additional restaurants, as it did not see value in such a strategy.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=54}} From 1930 through 1934 the company took over restaurants at [[\u00c5l Station|\u00c5l]], [[Jaren Station|Jaren]], [[Lillestr\u00f8m Station|Lillestr\u00f8m]] and [[T\u00f8nsberg Station|T\u00f8nsberg]], along with dining service on the steamship ''[[Skibladner]]'', which ran on [[Mj\u00f8sa]].{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=51}} During the first half of the 1940s it again acquired new restaurants, including the one at [[Kristiansand Station]].{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=54}} In 1940 and 1941 the company made a solid profit, but lack of food from 1942 onwards transformed the profit to a loss.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=55}} During the late 1940s NSS also took over the restaurants at [[Drammen Station|Drammen]] and [[Sarpsborg Station|Sarpsborg]], as well as the one at [[Oslo Airport, Fornebu]].{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=72}}\n\n==Hotels==\n[[File:Oppdal Turisthotell.jpg|thumb|left|Hotel at [[Oppdal Station]]|alt=Square, three-story hotel in winter]]\nIn 1919 the Norwegian Trunk Railway operated one hotel, which was built as part of [[Eidsvoll Station]]. Operation of the 20-room hotel was taken over by Spisevognselskapet on 14 October 1924.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=76}} NSB was at the time building the Dovre Line between Oslo and Trondheim, and was considering establishing hotels where the line passed through [[Dovrefjell]]. Both [[Hjerkinn Station|Hjerkinn]] and Fokkstua were considered, but these areas were served by other operators.{{Sfnm|Just|1949|1p=73|Adresseavisen|2009|2p=15}} Instead, Spisevognselskapet established the Oppdal Tourist Hotel adjacent to [[Oppdal Station]] and it opened on 28 June 1924.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=76}}{{Sfnm|H\u00f8gslund|1937|1p=55|Adresseavisen|2008|2p=28|Adresseavisen|2006|3p=17}} The 60-bed hotel had a floor area of {{convert|605|m2}}{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=79}} and was marketed as a tourist destination, with [[bobsleigh]] and [[curling]] during the winter and tennis and croquet in summer.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=80}} The hotel was closed for part of 1929, because the municipality would not allow it to serve alcoholic beverages.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=82}}\n\nIn Oslo, the company had its offices and workings spread around town. The main depot was at the East Station; the head office was at Fred. Olsens gate 21 from 1919 to 1921, at Kongens gate 29 until 1932, and at Tollbodgaten 24 until 1938. Management wanted to centralise both a new depot and administrative offices at a single location close to the railway station, preferably co-located with a hotel. In 1936 work began on a hotel at [[Jernbanetorget]], but the project was cancelled.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=91}} The proposed hotel would have had 100 rooms across the street from Oslo \u00d8. However, the plans were blocked by Parliament (which was opposed to the state railway operating hotels).{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=93}} Instead, the administration moved into Nylandsveien 10,{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=91}} in a new building built on a lot owned by NSB.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=93}}\n\nIn Bergen the company established Hotel Terminus Bergen along with other investors, but the hotel failed to make money.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=74}} In the late 1940s the company bought Grand Hotell Bellevue in [[\u00c5lesund]], and later operated Saltfjellet Tourist Hotel for a short period.{{Sfn|Thon|1993|p=242}} In 1952, Oslo Municipality's [[Hotel Royal Christiania|Viking Hotel]] was completed, and Spisevognselskapet was selected as the operator.{{Sfn|Verdens Gang|1951|p=8}} It remained the hotel's operator until 1976 when the government sold it to Eiendomsinvest, which outbid Spisevognselskapet by several million krone.{{Sfn|Verdens Gang|1976|p=16}}\n\n=={{anchor|Disestablishment}}Dissolution==\n[[File:Spisevogn carriage.jpg|thumb|Restaurant carriage in 1926|alt=Outside view of restaurant carriage]]\n[[Narvesen]] had an exclusive agreement with NSB to operate [[newsagent's shop]]s at all railway stations, except in stations with restaurants, which were operated by Spisevognselskapet. Narvesen had a near-monopoly on newsagents in Norway, and rented facilities in many public places. The owners of Narvesen intended to create a foundation to obtain the company; when plans for this started in 1972, they had difficulties finding a way to transfer shares to the foundation without having to pay tax on the transaction. However, the tax laws permitted a tax-free transaction if it was part of a restructuring.{{Sfn|Skedsmo|1993|p=134}} A merger with Spisevognselskapet would be considered a restructuring, and in 1974 [[Fritt Ord (organization)|Fritt Ord]] was established to take over Narvesen's owners' share of the company. The agreement between Narvesen and NSB was made in July 1974; in December it was passed by Parliament, although the [[Conservative Party (Norway)|Conservative Party]] and [[Progress Party (Norway)|Progress Party]] voted against the merger. A.S Narvesen\u2013Spisevognselskapet was established on 1 January 1975. Fritt Ord owned 50% of the new company and NSB 41%. It assumed the Narvesen name in 1979.{{Sfn|Skedsmo|1993|p=135}}\n\nBy the late 1980s, the company had sold all its hotel operations.{{Sfn|Thon|1993|p=242}} The merged company retained the obligation to operate dining services on the trains, which throughout the 1980s necessitated considerable subsidies from NSB. In 1988, NSB decided to organize the operation of the dining services through [[tendered]] contracts; the first contract (from 1990 through 1995) was won by TogService, a Narvesen subsidiary.{{Sfn|Skedsmo|1993|p=136}} The owners had an agreement that neither could sell without the approval of the other. In 1995 NSB sold its shares with Fritt Ord's approval, and the company was listed on the [[Oslo Stock Exchange]].{{Sfn|Fritt Ord|1997|pp=3\u20134}}\n\nIn 1999, Fritt Ord reduced its stock share in Narvesen from 51% to 34%. In the fall of 2000, Fritt Ord accepted a proposal to merge Narvesen with the [[Reitan Group]]. The merged company was named ReitanNarvesen; Fritt Ord held 16.2% of its shares.{{Sfn|Ottersland|2011|p=27}} In November 2001 Fritt Ord sold its shares of ReitanNarvesen,{{Sfn|Norwegian News Agency|2001}} which was renamed Reitan Handel{{Sfn|Norwegian News Agency|2002b}} and [[List of companies delisted from Oslo Stock Exchange|delisted from the Oslo Stock Exchange]].{{Sfn|Norwegian News Agency|2002a}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|colwidth=20em}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{commons category|Norsk Spisevognselskap}}\n;Books and journal articles\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Cite book |author=[[Fritt Ord (organization)|Fritt Ord]] |title=Institusjonen Fritt Ord |year=1997 |location=Oslo  |pages= |oclc=52544757 |language=Norwegian |ref={{SfnRef|Fritt Ord|1997}}}}\n*{{Cite book |last=H\u00f8gslund |first=O. |title=Dovrebanen og Tr\u00f8ndelag |year=1937 |publisher=[[Norwegian State Railways]] |edition=5th |series=Volume 7 of ''Norsk Reisebok'' |oclc=258361682 |language=Norwegian}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Just |first=Carl |title=A/S Norsk Spisevognselskap 1919\u20131949 |location=Oslo |publisher=Norsk Spisevognselskap |year=1949 |authorlink=Carl Just |oclc=40310643 |language=Norwegian |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Ottersland |first=Per Kristian |title=Uten mat og drikke... |journal=Arkivmagasinet |year=2011 |volume=11 |issue=1 |pages=24\u201327 |publisher=[[National Archival Services of Norway]] |issn=0801-5449 |language=Norwegian |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Skedsmo |first=Finn |title=Narvesen: Vindu mot verden i 100 \u00e5r |year=1993 |publisher=Narvesen |location=Bergen |isbn=82-7326-023-2 |language=Norwegian |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Thon |first=Sverre |title=Vertskap i Norge |year=1993 |publisher=Norsk hotell- og restaurantforbund |location=Oslo |isbn=82-992126-2-6 |language=Norwegian |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n;News articles and encyclopaedia entries\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Cite encyclopedia |title=Astrup, Sigurd |year=1935 |encyclopedia=[[Merkantilt biografisk leksikon]] |editor-last=Hoffstad |editor-first=Einar |editor-link=Einar Hoffstad |publisher=Yrkesforlaget |location=Oslo |url=http://runeberg.org/merkbio/0116.html |edition=1st |page=42 |accessdate=30 May 2011 |language=Norwegian |ref={{SfnRef|Hoffstad (ed.)|1935}}}}\n*{{Cite news |title=Hotellbygd i s\u00e6rklasse |newspaper=[[Adresseavisen]] |date=8 August 2009 |page=15 |language=Norwegian |ref={{SfnRef|Adresseavisen|2009}}}}\n*{{Cite news |title=Oppdal har urealiserte hotellplaner nok til en egen hotellkjede |newspaper=[[Adresseavisen]] |date=4 May 2006 |page=17 |language=Norwegian |ref={{SfnRef|Adresseavisen|2006}}}}\n*{{Cite news |title=Reitan Narvesen bytter navn |agency=[[Norwegian News Agency]] |date=18 February 2002 |language=Norwegian |ref={{SfnRef|Norwegian News Agency|2002b}}}}\n*{{Cite news |title=Reitan overtar Narvesen fra Fritt Ord |agency=[[Norwegian News Agency]] |date=15 November 2001 |language=Norwegian |ref={{SfnRef|Norwegian News Agency|2001}}}}\n*{{Cite news |title=Reitan tar hele kaka |agency=[[Norwegian News Agency]] |date=11 January 2002 |language=Norwegian |ref={{SfnRef|Norwegian News Agency|2002a}}}}\n*{{Cite news |title=Samvirkelaget inn i Viking? |newspaper=[[Verdens Gang]] |date=11 September 1976 |page=16 |language=Norwegian |ref={{SfnRef|Verdens Gang|1976}}}}\n*{{Cite news |title=Slik kom Oppdal p\u00e5 skinner |newspaper=[[Adresseavisen]] |date=19 March 2008 |page=28 |language=Norwegian |ref={{SfnRef|Adresseavisen|2008}}}}\n*{{Cite news |title=Spisevognselskapet fikk Viking Hotell |newspaper=[[Verdens Gang]] |date=2 August 1951 |page=8 |language=Norwegian |ref={{SfnRef|Verdens Gang|1951}}}}\n*{{Cite encyclopedia |title=Mossige, Erling |year=1973 |encyclopedia=Hvem er hvem? |editor-last=Steenstrup |editor-first=Bj\u00f8rn |publisher=Aschehoug |location=Oslo |url=http://runeberg.org/hvemerhvem/1973/0393.html |pages=393\u201394 |isbn=82-03-04886-2 |edition=11th |accessdate=30 May 2011 |language=Norwegian |ref={{SfnRef|Steenstrup (ed.)|1973}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Norsk Spisevognselskap}}\n[[Category:1918 establishments in Norway]]\n[[Category:Norwegian State Railways (1883\u20131996)]]\n[[Category:1975 disestablishments in Norway]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies of Norway]]\n[[Category:Hospitality companies established in 1918]]\n[[Category:Defunct hotel chains]]\n[[Category:Restaurant chains in Norway]]\n[[Category:Hotels in Norway]]\n[[Category:Norsk Spisevognselskap| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name   = Norsk Spisevognselskap\n| logo   = [[File:Norsk Spisevognselskap logo.png|200px]]\n| caption         =\n| type   = [[Statsforetak|State enterprise]]\n| fate           = [[Mergers and acquisitions|Merger]]\n| Predecessor    =\n| successor      = [[Narvesen]]\n| foundation     = 21 December 1918\n| defunct        = 1 January 1975\n| location       = [[Oslo]], [[Norway]]\n| industry       = [[Rail transport]]\n| products       = [[Mobile catering]]\n| key_people     =\n| num_employees  = 591 (1949){{Sfn|Ottersland|2011|p=25}}\n| parent         = [[Norwegian State Railways]]\n| subsid         =\n}}\n\n'''Norsk Spisevognselskap A/S''', often abbreviated '''NSS''' or shortened to '''Spisevognselskapet''', was a [[Norway|Norwegian]] [[government-owned corporation|state enterprise]] which operated [[restaurant carriage]]s on [[rail transport in Norway|Norwegian trains]] and restaurants at [[railway station]]s and [[Hotel#Railway hotels|railway hotels]]. The company was established in December 1918, and started a catering service in 1919. Originally owned by the [[Hoved Line|Norwegian Trunk Railway]], it was acquired by the state in 1926. Meals served in the restaurant carriages were relatively expensive, although they were available to all passengers. In the 1950s, the company began using serving trolleys on trains.\n\nIn January 1975, NSS [[Mergers and acquisitions|merged]] with the convenience-store chain [[Narvesen|Narvesen Kioskkompani]] into a new company called Narvesen\u2013Spisevognselskapet. This enterprise was partly owned by the [[Norwegian State Railways]] (NSB) and [[Fritt Ord (organization)|Fritt Ord]], before it merged with the [[Reitan Group]] and was delisted from the [[Oslo Stock Exchange]].\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Spisevognbergensbanen.jpg|thumb|left|Restaurant carriage on a [[Bergen Line]] train in 1909|alt=restaurant carriage, with tables set for dinner]]\nFrom the 1854 establishment of railways in Norway to 1909, no dining service was offered aboard trains; passengers were allowed to bring food with them. Train stations also lacked dining facilities. The first dining service was started by restaurateur Carl Christiansen.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=13}} He established the restaurant at [[Drammen Station]], and in 1907 was asked by NSB to establish a dining service aboard the express trains on the [[Bergen Line]], which would open in 1909. After investigating similar operations in England and Germany, he ordered two carriages from [[Skabo Jernbanevognfabrikk]].{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=14}} These were to be paid for by the state, but the [[Parliament of Norway]] delayed the grants after a long debate regarding the suitability of restaurant carriages on trains. The plans were opposed by the [[Teetotalism|teetotaler]] faction of Parliament, but there was a majority in favor of dining service. To get the carriages in time, Christiansen personally guaranteed the production cost in case a state grant was not allocated. After the parliamentary decision, the cost of the carriages was refunded by NSB.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=15}} In 1910, when [[President of the United States]] [[Theodore Roosevelt]] visited [[Oslo]] to receive the [[Nobel Peace Prize]], several restaurant carriages were ordered solely for the occasion. Two years later, restaurant carriages were put in regular service on the [[\u00d8stfold Line]].{{Sfn|Ottersland|2011|p=24}}\n\n==Early days==\n[[File:Norsk Spisevognselskap at Oslo \u00d8.jpg|thumb|Norsk Spisevognselskap restaurant carriage at [[Oslo East Station]] in 1935|alt=Outside of restaurant carriage, 1935]]\nIn 1916, the executive board of the state railways wanted to centralise the operation of restaurant carriages and the most important station restaurants in Norway under one management. The board stated that they wanted to minimise the conflict of interest between the railway company and the dining-car operator. They also saw centralising operations as a way to allocate a larger share of the revenue to the railway company, and to ensure a high quality of service on new lines.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=22}} At that time the [[S\u00f8rland Line]] and [[Dovre Line]] were in the planning stages, and the NSB intended to introduce dining services on these when they opened.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=28}} [[Oslo East Station]] and its restaurant were operated by the private [[Hoved Line|Norwegian Trunk Railway]]. In an agreement signed on 18 September 1918 both railway companies agreed that a new restaurant operator would be controlled by the Norwegian Trunk Railway, but this company had to abide by the NSB's decision of how many restaurant carriages to operate on any line.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=23}}\n\nThis model was inspired by Sweden, where a separate dining company had been established; this company paid the railway company part of its revenue and a fixed fee per restaurant carriage. The Swedish model involved including the operation of station restaurants at locations where the restaurant carriages would have depots.<!--What does the word \"depots\" mean in this sentence?-->{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=29}} On 21 December 1918, A.S Norsk Spisevognselskap was established with a share capital of 200,000 [[Norwegian krone]] (NOK). It had 20 shares; 17 were owned by the Trunk Railway, and one by each of three directors: [[Waldemar Stoud Platou]], Gotfred Furuholmen and [[Christian Emil Stoud Platou]]\u2014the former representing the Trunk Railway and the latter being director-general of the NSB.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=24}} In January 1919, Waldemar Platou was appointed chair and Christiansen managing director. The company took over Christiansen's four restaurant carriages and the restaurant at Oslo \u00d8 on 1 April 1919.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=27}}\n\nOn 2 February 1926, Parliament voted to [[nationalise]] the Trunk Railway. During the debate, the organisation of Spisevognselskapet was criticised; with the nationalisation, the state became the sole owner of Spisevognselskapet. On 31 March 1927, the [[Ministry of Labour (Norway 1885\u20131946)|Ministry of Labour]] recommended that the company remain a state-owned limited company; the minority in parliament wanted a state enterprise.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=31}} During the 1930s, [[Sigurd Astrup]] was managing director of Norsk Spisevognselskap.{{Sfn|Hoffstad (ed.)|1935|p=42}} In 1948, [[Erling Mossige]] was appointed managing director of the company. He was succeeded by [[Knut Tvedt]] in 1960.{{Sfn|Steenstrup (ed.)|1973|pp=393\u201394}} The company had 75 employees in 1919, and 591 in 1949.{{Sfn|Ottersland|2011|p=25}}\n\n==Restaurant carriages==\n[[File:Norsk Spisevognselskap dining in 1947.jpg|thumb|left|Dining in 1947|alt=Waiter serving party of four in 1947]]\nThe restaurant carriages of the NSS were open to everyone, but dining was so expensive that only passengers travelling in first class used the service. Usually, three or four dishes were offered in the restaurant carriages. A four-course dinner cost five [[Norwegian kroner]] in the 1920s, which was expensive at the time.{{Sfn|Ottersland|2011|p=26}} Warm dishes, such as soups and sauces, were usually prepared at a small stove in the restaurant carriage's kitchen. On busy days, prepared steaks were delivered from rail depots. The kitchens were staffed by two maids and one attendant. Blocks of ice were often used instead of [[refrigerator]]s.{{Sfn|Ottersland|2011|p=26}}\n\nWith the opening of the Dovre Line, Spisevognselskapet established dining-car service on 25 June 1921.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=39}} In 1921 a train ride from Kristiania to [[Trondheim]] lasted approximately 15 hours, and the average waiting time at each station was between 10 and 15 minutes.{{Sfn|Ottersland|2011|p=26}} On 1 July 1925 dining service was introduced on the [[Valdres Line]], from 1 July 1926 on the [[Brevik Line]], from May 1934 on the [[Nordland Line]] and from 15 May 1936 on the [[R\u00f8ros Line]]. In 1948 210,000 meals were served on board, in addition to sandwiches and drinks. The company also offered a light breakfast on night trains on the [[Kongsvinger Line|Kongsvinger]], \u00d8stfold and Dovre lines.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=39}} During the [[Second World War]], dining-car service was discontinued.\n\nAfter the war trains faced competition from [[aviation]] and automobiles, and serving trolleys were installed on Norwegian trains.{{Sfn|Ottersland|2011|p=26}} In 1965 cart service on trains was centralised and standardised; food service was faster, and prices were lowered. During the 1970s cafeteria cars were used, where passengers could serve themselves.{{Sfn|Ottersland|2011|p=26}}\n\n==Restaurants==\n[[File:Bjorli restaurant.jpg|thumb|Restaurant at [[Bjorli Station]]|alt=Large, high-ceilinged restaurant in Bjorli Station]]\nNSS derived most of its revenue from the operation of restaurants at railway stations; in 1939, this amounted to 80%.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=49}} Initially, the company operated the restaurant at Oslo \u00d8; from 1921, it also took over operation of the restaurants at [[Oslo Vestbanestasjon|Oslo West Station]], [[Hamar Station|Hamar]], [[Koppang Station|Koppang]], [[Oppdal Station|Opdal]] and [[Elverum Station|Elverum]]. The following year, four more restaurants were added: [[St\u00f8ren Station|St\u00f8ren]], [[Myrdal Station|Myrdal]], [[Dokka Station|Dokka]] and [[Hell Station|Hell]]. NSS also established its first kiosk, at [[Bergen Station]].{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=50}} In 1923, the company was allowed to take over all restaurants in the railway districts of Oslo and Hamar; by 1925, it had taken over operation of the restaurants at [[Lillehammer Station|Lillehammer]], [[H\u00f8nefoss Station|H\u00f8nefoss]], [[Jessheim Station|Jessheim]], [[Kornsj\u00f8 Station|Kornsj\u00f8]], [[Halden Station|Halden]], [[Ski Station|Ski]], [[Eidsvoll Station|Eidsvoll]], [[Otta Station|Otta]], [[Domb\u00e5s Station|Domb\u00e5s]], [[\u00c5ndalsnes Station|\u00c5ndalsnes]], [[Kongsvinger Station|Kongsvinger]], [[Trondheim Central Station|Trondheim]], [[Rena Station|Rena]], [[Roa Station|Roa]], [[Ringebu Station|Ringebu]], [[Bjorli Station|Bjorli]] and [[Finse Station|Finse]].{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=51}}\n\nAfter this NSS decided not to obtain many additional restaurants, as it did not see value in such a strategy.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=54}} From 1930 through 1934 the company took over restaurants at [[\u00c5l Station|\u00c5l]], [[Jaren Station|Jaren]], [[Lillestr\u00f8m Station|Lillestr\u00f8m]] and [[T\u00f8nsberg Station|T\u00f8nsberg]], along with dining service on the steamship ''[[Skibladner]]'', which ran on [[Mj\u00f8sa]].{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=51}} During the first half of the 1940s it again acquired new restaurants, including the one at [[Kristiansand Station]].{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=54}} In 1940 and 1941 the company made a solid profit, but lack of food from 1942 onwards transformed the profit to a loss.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=55}} During the late 1940s NSS also took over the restaurants at [[Drammen Station|Drammen]] and [[Sarpsborg Station|Sarpsborg]], as well as the one at [[Oslo Airport, Fornebu]].{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=72}}\n\n==Hotels==\n[[File:Oppdal Turisthotell.jpg|thumb|left|Hotel at [[Oppdal Station]]|alt=Square, three-story hotel in winter]]\nIn 1919 the Norwegian Trunk Railway operated one hotel, which was built as part of [[Eidsvoll Station]]. Operation of the 20-room hotel was taken over by Spisevognselskapet on 14 October 1924.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=76}} NSB was at the time building the Dovre Line between Oslo and Trondheim, and was considering establishing hotels where the line passed through [[Dovrefjell]]. Both [[Hjerkinn Station|Hjerkinn]] and Fokkstua were considered, but these areas were served by other operators.{{Sfnm|Just|1949|1p=73|Adresseavisen|2009|2p=15}} Instead, Spisevognselskapet established the Oppdal Tourist Hotel adjacent to [[Oppdal Station]] and it opened on 28 June 1924.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=76}}{{Sfnm|H\u00f8gslund|1937|1p=55|Adresseavisen|2008|2p=28|Adresseavisen|2006|3p=17}} The 60-bed hotel had a floor area of {{convert|605|m2}}{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=79}} and was marketed as a tourist destination, with [[bobsleigh]] and [[curling]] during the winter and tennis and croquet in summer.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=80}} The hotel was closed for part of 1929, because the municipality would not allow it to serve alcoholic beverages.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=82}}\n\nIn Oslo, the company had its offices and workings spread around town. The main depot was at the East Station; the head office was at Fred. Olsens gate 21 from 1919 to 1921, at Kongens gate 29 until 1932, and at Tollbodgaten 24 until 1938. Management wanted to centralise both a new depot and administrative offices at a single location close to the railway station, preferably co-located with a hotel. In 1936 work began on a hotel at [[Jernbanetorget]], but the project was cancelled.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=91}} The proposed hotel would have had 100 rooms across the street from Oslo \u00d8. However, the plans were blocked by Parliament (which was opposed to the state railway operating hotels).{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=93}} Instead, the administration moved into Nylandsveien 10,{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=91}} in a new building built on a lot owned by NSB.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=93}}\n\nIn Bergen the company established Hotel Terminus Bergen along with other investors, but the hotel failed to make money.{{Sfn|Just|1949|p=74}} In the late 1940s the company bought Grand Hotell Bellevue in [[\u00c5lesund]], and later operated Saltfjellet Tourist Hotel for a short period.{{Sfn|Thon|1993|p=242}} In 1952, Oslo Municipality's [[Hotel Royal Christiania|Viking Hotel]] was completed, and Spisevognselskapet was selected as the operator.{{Sfn|Verdens Gang|1951|p=8}} It remained the hotel's operator until 1976 when the government sold it to Eiendomsinvest, which outbid Spisevognselskapet by several million krone.{{Sfn|Verdens Gang|1976|p=16}}\n\n=={{anchor|Disestablishment}}Dissolution==\n[[File:Spisevogn carriage.jpg|thumb|Restaurant carriage in 1926|alt=Outside view of restaurant carriage]]\n[[Narvesen]] had an exclusive agreement with NSB to operate [[newsagent's shop]]s at all railway stations, except in stations with restaurants, which were operated by Spisevognselskapet. Narvesen had a near-monopoly on newsagents in Norway, and rented facilities in many public places. The owners of Narvesen intended to create a foundation to obtain the company; when plans for this started in 1972, they had difficulties finding a way to transfer shares to the foundation without having to pay tax on the transaction. However, the tax laws permitted a tax-free transaction if it was part of a restructuring.{{Sfn|Skedsmo|1993|p=134}} A merger with Spisevognselskapet would be considered a restructuring, and in 1974 [[Fritt Ord (organization)|Fritt Ord]] was established to take over Narvesen's owners' share of the company. The agreement between Narvesen and NSB was made in July 1974; in December it was passed by Parliament, although the [[Conservative Party (Norway)|Conservative Party]] and [[Progress Party (Norway)|Progress Party]] voted against the merger. A.S Narvesen\u2013Spisevognselskapet was established on 1 January 1975. Fritt Ord owned 50% of the new company and NSB 41%. It assumed the Narvesen name in 1979.{{Sfn|Skedsmo|1993|p=135}}\n\nBy the late 1980s, the company had sold all its hotel operations.{{Sfn|Thon|1993|p=242}} The merged company retained the obligation to operate dining services on the trains, which throughout the 1980s necessitated considerable subsidies from NSB. In 1988, NSB decided to organize the operation of the dining services through [[tendered]] contracts; the first contract (from 1990 through 1995) was won by TogService, a Narvesen subsidiary.{{Sfn|Skedsmo|1993|p=136}} The owners had an agreement that neither could sell without the approval of the other. In 1995 NSB sold its shares with Fritt Ord's approval, and the company was listed on the [[Oslo Stock Exchange]].{{Sfn|Fritt Ord|1997|pp=3\u20134}}\n\nIn 1999, Fritt Ord reduced its stock share in Narvesen from 51% to 34%. In the fall of 2000, Fritt Ord accepted a proposal to merge Narvesen with the [[Reitan Group]]. The merged company was named ReitanNarvesen; Fritt Ord held 16.2% of its shares.{{Sfn|Ottersland|2011|p=27}} In November 2001 Fritt Ord sold its shares of ReitanNarvesen,{{Sfn|Norwegian News Agency|2001}} which was renamed Reitan Handel{{Sfn|Norwegian News Agency|2002b}} and [[List of companies delisted from Oslo Stock Exchange|delisted from the Oslo Stock Exchange]].{{Sfn|Norwegian News Agency|2002a}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|colwidth=20em}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{commons category|Norsk Spisevognselskap}}\n;Books and journal articles\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Cite book |author=[[Fritt Ord (organization)|Fritt Ord]] |title=Institusjonen Fritt Ord |year=1997 |location=Oslo  |pages= |oclc=52544757 |language=Norwegian |ref={{SfnRef|Fritt Ord|1997}}}}\n*{{Cite book |last=H\u00f8gslund |first=O. |title=Dovrebanen og Tr\u00f8ndelag |year=1937 |publisher=[[Norwegian State Railways]] |edition=5th |series=Volume 7 of ''Norsk Reisebok'' |oclc=258361682 |language=Norwegian}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Just |first=Carl |title=A/S Norsk Spisevognselskap 1919\u20131949 |location=Oslo |publisher=Norsk Spisevognselskap |year=1949 |authorl